ONE ( 55 GAL ) DRUM WAS PUNCTURED AT BASE BY A FORKLIFT BLADE, WHEN A DOCKMAN ( MIKE GROTHEER ) WAS UNLOADING CARTONS OF PIECE GOODS THAT WERE BEHIND THE DRUMS ( THERE WASN'T ANY DUNNAGE BETWEEN THE DRUMS & PC. GOODS ) .  AFTER FINDING THE DRUM TO BE HAZARDOUS ( SECONDS AFTER THE INCIDENT ) , I PULLED THE TRAILER DOOR DOWN ( INSTRUCTING EVERYONE TO STAY OUT & AROUND TRAILER ) AND CALLED ALAN LOVE IN HUMAN DEVELOPMENT/RISK MANAGEMENT TO REPORT SPILL.  ALAN HAD ME REPORT SPILL TO CHEMTREC AND HAVE CHEMTREC FAX MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS ON DAMAGED PRODUCT.  AFTER GOING OVER THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS AND DUE TO THE STRONG ODOR IN TRAILER, ALAN INSTRUCTED ME TO  CALL A CHEMICAL RESPONSE TEAM ( HEPACO ) FOR CLEAN UP OF SPILL.

AT APPROXIMATELY 3:45PM ON AUGUST 2 WE RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT THEY HAD RECEIVED A CALL COMPLAINING OF A FOUL ODOR IN THE AREA OF ESPLANADE AVENUE AND THE RAILROAD TRACKS. THEIR INVESTIGATION FOUND A TANK CAR, GATX 15458, WHICH WAS ON NOPB MAIN TRACK AT MILE POST 10 WAS THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  THIS CAR CONTAINED DIMETHYL SULPHIDE.  WE IMPLEMENTED OUR HAZ-MAT RESPONSE PLAN AND NOTIFIED ALL APPROPRIATE AGENCIES.

THIS DAMAGE OCCURRED IN THE ACCEPTING STATION DURING THEIR SORT PROCEDURES.  THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST CLEANED AND CONTAINED THE SPILL PER FEDEX POLICY AND PROCEDURE.  THE PACKAGE WILL BE PLACED IN A SECURE HOLDING AREA UNTIL DISPOSITION INFORMATION IS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

column168: CAR STANDING IN YARD REPORTED LEAKING. BNSF RESPONDER FOUND THAT THERMAL EXPANSION OF PRODUCT DURING THE DAYLIGHT HOURS HAD FORCED PRODUCT THROUGH THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. RESPONDER LOOSENED MANWAY COVER BOLTS TO EQUALIZE PRESSURE. AFTER PRESSURE EQUALIZED, PRODUCT ESCAPE STOPPED & MANWAY COVER BOLTS RETIGHTENED. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS WIPED. CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION. SHIPPER TO BE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT.

CAR STANDING ON REPAIR TRACK FOR COUPLER ASSEMBLY DEFECTS REPORTED EMANATING PRODUCT ODOR. BNSF RESPONDERS CHECKED CAR & COULD NOT FIND ANY OBVIOUS DEFECTS. SHIPPER REPRESENTIVES RESPONDED & FOUND LOOSE PACKING NUT ON GAUGING ROD. PACKING CHECKED & PACKING NUT TIGHTENED, ELIMINATING ODOR. CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTER REPAIRS COMPLETED.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Liner; Piping or Fittings
column168: BNSF CONDUCTOR SPLASHED ON ARMS BY RELEASED PRODUCT DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS. EMPLOYEE TREATED FOR CHEMICAL SKIN IRRITATION WITH SALVE AT MEDICAL CENTER & RELEASED WITH NO LOST WORK DAYS. EMPLOYEE WEARING ALL APPROPRIATE PPE AT THE TIME. BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND ONE MANWAY BOLT  NOT APPLIED & THE OTHERS LOOSE 2 1/2 TURNS EACH. THIS ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SLOSH OUT MANWAY DURING CAR MOVEMENT. BOLTS APPLIED/TIGHTENED & SPILLED PRODUCT ON CAR REMEDIATED.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: WHEN INVESTIGATING ANOTHER CAR, IT WAS NOTICED THAT UTLX 46951 WAS EMITTING A STRONG ODOR. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS VENTING. THE VALVE WAS REMOVED AND WAS OBSERVED TO BE DIRTY. THEREBY NOT ALLOWING THE VALVE TO SEAT AND CLOSE PROPERLY. THE VALVE SEAT WAS CLEANED AND THE VALVE WAS PLACED BACK ON THE CAR. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: ONE DRUM FELL ON IT'S SIDE WHILE IN TRANSIT. THE DRUM RECEIVED A SMALL PUNCTURE TO IT'S SIDE WHERE IT RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES INTO THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED DRUM SHORTLY AFTER AND ROLLED IT ONTO IT'S SIDE PREVENTING FURTHER LEAKAGE. ADVANCED RESPONSE CORPORATION IN MEMPHIS, TN WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE FOR CLEANUP PROCEDURES. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN DISCIPLINED FOR FAILING TO SECURE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FROM MOVEMENT DURING TRANSIT.

TRAILER IN PROCESS OF UNLOADING WHEN CUSTOMERS STORAGE BECAME FULL. CUSTOMER DECIDED TO PUT BALANCE OF MATERIAL INTO TOTES. TO FACILATE THE UNLOADING INTO TOTES A DRUMMING NOZZLE WAS BEING USED. WHEN DRUM NOZZLE WAS SHUT OFF IT CREATED BACK PRESSURE ON HOSE  THAT CAUSED HOSE TO RUPTURE BEFORE PUMP BY PASS COULD ENGAGE. RUPTURE OF HOSE CAUSED APPROXIMATELY (50) FIFTY GALLONS SPILL ONTO CARRIERS TRACTOR AND TRAILER (SPRAY). MATERIAL CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY PERSONNEL OF MONARCH PAINT CO.

column168: WE SPOTTED TWO TRAILERS AT ASHLAND DISTRIBUTION COMPANY'S FACILITY; AFTER THEY LOADED AND SECURED THEIR FREIGHT WE WERE CALLED TO PICKUP THE TRAILERS ON 8-04-00. ON 8-05-00 OUR DRIVER EN ROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION TERMINAL PULLED THIS SET INTO A REST AREA TO TAKE A COFFEE BREAK. WHEN HE GOT OUT HIS TRACTOR HE SMELLED A STRONG CHEMICAL ODOR. HE IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE SPILL TO THE COMPANY. WE NOTIFIED OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CLEANUP JOBBER WHO REPORTED TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST OUR CREW IN SECURING AND CLEANING UP THE 5-GALLON SPILLAGE. NOTE: THE CONTENTS OF THE CRUSHED PAIL EVAPORATED. THERE WERE 3 ADDITIONAL DAMAGED PAILS BUT NONE WERE LEAKING THAT WE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER WITH THE CRUSHED CONTAINER (IN TWO RECOVERY DRUMS). DURING THE CLEANUP THE INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE FREIGHT WAS IMPROPERLY SECURED. IT WAS NOTED THAT THERE WAS A GAP ALONG THE SIDEWALL AND THE FREIGHT ALLOWING THE SHIFTING  OF A STACKED PALLET THAT PUT STRESS ON THE PAILS BENEATH IT -- CAUSING ONE 5-GALLON PAIL TO BE CRUSHED LOSING IT CONTENTS, AND DAMAGING 3 OTHER PAILS THAT DID NOT LEAK.WE WILL PRESENT OUR FINDINGS TO THE SHIPPER. TO INSURE PROPER LOADING AND SECURING.

OUR DRIVER STOPPED AT OUR LAKE CHARLES LA. TERMINAL TO CHECK OUT HIS TRACTOR AIR CONDITIONER AS HE WALKING BY THE TRAILER HE  DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BELLY OF OUR TRAILER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE FLANGE WAS LEAKING WE TRANSFERED THE PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER TRAILER WITH NO PROBLEMS.

DRIVER COMPLETED UNLOADING INTO CONSIGNEE STORAGE TANK. HE FAILED TO BLEED-OFF AIR PRESSURE IN THE  DELIVERY HOSES AND ON REMOVING HOSE FROM FITTING,  MATERIAL SPRAYED OUT. DRIVER HAD PRODUCT ON HIS FACE. FACILITY PERSONNEL PLACED HIM IN SAFETY SHOWER & THEN TRANSPORTED HIM TO THE GOODING COUNTY MEDICAL HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT HE HAS BEEN RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK ON 8-17-00.

column168: ON AUGUST 4, 2000 A 30 GALLON 1H1/Y1.9/150/99/USA/M5174/2.2MM/P30/M-93/114/L/USG POLY DRUM FAILED WHILE ON A CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC'S. (CHESI) VAN TRAILER PARKED AT KING INDUSTRIES, SCIENCE ROAD, IN NORWALK, CT 06852 CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND. THE MATERIAL WAS WASTE, SULFURIC ACID, 8 UN2796, PGII WHICH WAS LOADED AT THE PREVIOUS STOP AT PHOTRONICS INC. 15 SECOR DRIVE, IN BROOKFIELD, CT 06804. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW FROM CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDED AND IMMEDIATELY PLACED THE FAILED DRUM IN A POLY OVER PACK AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL AREA. THE CAUSE OF THE FAILURE WAS PRESSURE BUILDUP INSIDE THE CONTAINER. CHESI PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN REMINDED THE IMPORTANCE OF VISUALLY INSPECTING THE INTEGRITY OF ALL POLY CONTAINERS FOR ABNORMALITIES, ESPECIALLY THE SIDES AND THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINERS TO ENSURE THERE IS NO BULGING AND THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINERS ARE NOT ROUNDED.

column168: THE SHIPPER DID NOT ALLOW FOR PROPER ULLAGE. EXPOSURE TO HEAT FROM THE SUN CAUSED CHEMICAL TO EXPAND. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED ON SITE BY SWS, AND PRODUCT WILL BE SCHEDULED FOR DISPOSAL AT AN EPA APPROVED SITE.

UNLOADER NOTIFIED ME OF WET PACKAGE. I NOTICED IT WAS A DIAMOND LABEL CORROSIVE. WEARING FULL PPE I FOLLOWED DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEETS FOR A CORROSIVE SPILL. SPILL WAS CLEANED WITH SODIUM CARBONATE & PH TESTED TILL NEUTRAL. PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN SPILL TUB & BROUGHT TO PROCESSING AREA. I PACKAGED THE WASTE THROUGH DMP. MERCHANDISE RTS'D TO SHIPPER. PACKAGE WAS IMPROPERLY LOADED & CONSEQUENTLY STRUCK BY OTHER FREIGHT. THEN LATER DECONTAMINATED (CLEANED) THE P.P.E AS INSTRUCTED. SALVAGED MERCHANDISE WAS R.T.S'D THRU UPS SALVAGE DRUM.

THIS PARTICULAR BOX WAS STAGED ON OUR DOCK  FLOOR BY AN UPRIGHT SUPPORT POLE AND WHEN A DOCK WORKER WAS STAGING A PALLET BY  IT HE HIT THE BOX PINNING IT BETWEEN THE FREIGHT HE WAS STAGING AND THE POLE. THIS SUBSEQUENTLY CAUSED ONE OF THE INNER BOTTLES TO RUPTURE AND SPILL CONTENTS. SPILLED MATERIAL LITERALLY EVAPORATED WHEN ATTEMPTED TO CLEAN UP. REMAINDER OF FREIGHT WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND SENT TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.

WHEN UNLOADING FREIGHT, DOCKWORKER FOUND THIS ONE BAG OF RESORCINOL SLIGHTLY RIPPED OPENED AND SMALL SPILLAGE ON TRAILER FLOOR. IT APPEARS THAT A PALLET LOADED NEXT TO IT RIPPED THE BAG OPENED WHEN LOADED ONTO TRAILER.... CARDBORAD INBETWEEN THE TWO SHIPMENTS PROBABLY COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS. SPILLED CONTENTS AND RIPPED BAG WHERE PLACED INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND ARE AWAITING DISPOSITION.
DRIVER MISJUDGED THE DISTANCE OF THE FRT & STRUCK DRUM WITH FORK LIFT BLADES. DRUM WAS PUT ON ITS SIDE TO STOP LEAKING VERY LITTLE LOSS OF PRODUCT.

AS NOTED AT TIME OF FREIGHT COMING INTO TERMINAL 1 TANK APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING OFF THE LINE HAUL UNIT. FLOOR WAS WET. TANK REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND SET ON CARDBOARD. IT WAS SURROUNDED BY 4 BAGS OF OIL DRY COMPLETELY AROUND THE TANK. CHEM-TEC WAS CALLED FOR EMERGENCY NOTIFICATION. K& D RESPONDED TO CLEAN THE SPILLAGE.

A TON CONTAINER WAS RETURNED TO OUR FACILITY FROM A CUSTOMER'S LOCATION.  IT WAS INSPECTED AND REFILLED.  WE LOADED IT ON OUR FLATBED DELIVERY VEHICLE ALONG WITH SEVERAL OTHERS FOR A DELIVERY ON 08/07/00.  IT WAS PARKED IN OUR YARD FROM 8/4/00 - 8/6/00 WHEN THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED.  AT 9:30PM ON A CALL TO 911 ALERTED POLICE & FIRE OFFICIALS OF THE LEAK.  OUR RESPONDERS WERE CALLED & ALONG WITH THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. HANDLED THE SITUATION.  SUBURBAN DR, WHICH IS A RURAL, SECONDARY RD WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS.  ALL OF THE AREA WHERE THE SPILL WAS, WAS DECONTAMINATED & DISPOSED OF NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT TO THE SOIL.  AFTER INVESTIGATING THE CAUSE, IT WAS FOUND THAT THE TON CONTAINED 118LBS OF WATER, THIS CREATED HCL ACID IN IT, THAT ATE THE THREADS ON THE FUSE PLUG.  APPROXIMATELY 1865LBS OF CHLORINE WAS RELEASED THROUGH A HOLE IN THE THREADS MEASURING APPROX 1/8".  THIS TOOK AN ESTIMATED 4 HOURS.  NO EVACUATIONS NECESSARY.  WE HAVE INSTITUTED NEW PROCEDURES TO DETECT WATER IN RETURNED TONS THAT WILL ELIMINATE THIS FROM RECURRING.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER BOX WAS FOUND TO HAVE SEVERAL LARGE HYPODERMIC NEEDLES PROTRUDING THROUGH SIDE OF BOX. BOX WAS OPEN AND NEEDLES WERE NOT FOUND IN PROPER SHARPS CONTAINERS. WASTE WAS REPACKAGED FORE PROPER SAFE DISPOSAL. SALES WILL NOTIFY CUSTOMER TO INSURE THAT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT WILL NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

WHILE LOADING, ONE DAMAGED 300-GALLON POLY TOTE TANK WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER.APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE TOTE TANK WAS PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. TERMINAL PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE FREE PRODUCT WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS. TERMINAL PERSONNEL TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING PRODUCT INTO 95 GALLON OVERPACK DRUMS. GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL OF NEW ORLEANS, LOUISIANA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM ADDITIONAL CLEANUP. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. ALL STATE AND  LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column42: REGULATED MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR CLINICAL WASTE, UNSPECIFIED, N.O.S. OR (BIO) MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S., OR BIOMEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S. OR MEDICAL WASTE, N.O.S.
column168: WHILE TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED CONTAINERS WERE FOUND TIPPED OVER DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING/ BRACING. BLOOD CONTAINER HAD SPILLED AND WASTE HAD SPILLED DUE TO INNER PACKAGE NOT BEING PROPERLY CLOSED. WASTE WAS REPACKAGED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AND TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED. SALES WILL CONTACT CUSTOMER TO INSURE THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT DOES NOT HAPPEN AGAIN.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED, 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY THIRTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND KITTY LITTER. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 70 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A 60 GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM. THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TERMINAL, TWO LEAKING 55-GALLON DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DRUMS WERE LEAKING DUE TO PACKAGING FAILURE.TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP BY PLACING THE HARDENED PRODUCT ONTO A PIECE OF CARDBOARD. THE CARDBOARD AND HARDENED PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO THE GENERAL WASTE RECEPTACLE. THE TWO LEAKING DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO TWO RECOVERY DRUMS.THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE LOADING, ONE DAMAGED, FIVE-GALLON PAIL WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY A HALF GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND AFFECTED SOME DUNNAGE AND SHRINKWRAP. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE-GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. THE DAMAGED PAIL, AFFECTED SHRINKWRAP AND AFFECTED DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column25: DU PONT E I DE NEMOURS & CO
column168: WHEN THE TRAILER ARRIVED AT THE TERMINAL, TERMINAL PERSONNEL NOTICED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 4.5 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CAN WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PLACED THE DAMAGED CAN INTO A THIRTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE SHIPPER, E.I.  DUPONT DEMOURS, SENT A TEAM OUT TO PERFORM ADDITIONAL CLEANUP.  E.I. DUPONT DEMOURS IS SENDING A TRAILER TO PICK UP THE REMAINING FREIGHT ON THE TRAILER AND THE RECOVERY DRUM.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
column172: Metal can, capacity 7 gallons or less

column168: WHILE LOADING, AN ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND AIRED OUT OVERNIGHT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL THEN WENT INTO THE TRAILER TO INVESTIGATE.  UPON INVESTIGATION, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING ONE, ONE QUART GLASS JAR WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE JAR WAS BROKEN.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND EVAPORATED.  APPARENTLY THE JAR WAS BROKEN DUE TO BEING DROPPED IN HANDLING.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, A BROOM, AND A DUSTPAN.  THE WET CARTON AND BROKEN JAR WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXP0SURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON, CONTAINING ONE DAMAGED, ONE GALLON GLASS BOTTLE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE BOTTLE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING DURING TRANSIT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES.  THE DAMAGED BOTTLE, WET CARTON, AND GLOVES WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED 55 POUND PAPER BAG WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FIRST QUARTER MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED..APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE BAG WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED BAG, AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A POLY RECOUP BAG.  THE RECOUP BAG WILL BE HELD BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

THIS PRODUCT HAD ALREADY BEEN LOADED INTO TRAILER PRIOR TO INCIDENT. ANOTHER SKID WAS PLACED DIRECTLY BEHIND WITH NO PROBLEM; HOWEVER, STACKE ATTEMPTED TO LOAD A SKID ON TOP OF THE SKID IN FRONT OF THE AETOFINA PRODUCT. BEING THAT THE SKID WAS LARGER THAN THE ONE IT WAS BEING PLACE UPON, THE PERTRUDING FRT PUNCTURED THE CTN OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. SPILLED MATERIALS WAS CAPTURED ON DUNAGE BELOW PRODUCT AND WAS PLACED INTO AN OPEN TOP 30-GAL CONTAINER (PER CHEMTREC) FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

DRUM WAS FOUND IN THE DOCK BAY TO BE LEAKING. UNLOADING ASSOCIATE WAS UNAWARE OF INCIDENT UNTIL CALLED TO HIS ATTENTION. STRIPPING TRAILER INSPECTED FOR SPILLAGE, NO EVIDENCE FOUND. MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SEEPED OUT OF 3/8" CRACK IN PLASTIC DRUM AT BOTTOM EDGE. SEALED CRACK WITH BONDING AGENT.(EPOXY)

DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY FORK LIFT MASK. DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAYED ON SIDE TO CONTROL LEAKAGE. APPROXIMATELY 1 QT. EXCAPED DURING PROCESS. DRUM WAS PATCHED WITH EPOXY PUTTING AND HELD TO CURE FOR 24 HRS. RESIDUE WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN 5 GAL CONTAINER FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
SEQUENCE OF EVENTS: UNKNOWN ACTION @ TIME: UNKNOWN ACTION FOR FUTURE: MORE PACKAGING, PROPER DOT LABELS.

STRINGFELLOW SAID, "THE BULK (OF THE WASTE OILS) WAS STILL IN TANKER. NOTHING GOT IN THE WATER OR STEAM" OF NEARBY LAUREL RUN.  THE RIGHT LANE OF WESTBOUND ROUTE 322 WAS CLOSED AND POLICE SAID THE LANE REMAINED CLOSED UNTIL THE TRUCK WAS REMOVED LATE TUESDAY EVENING.  LUCAS SAID PENNDOT AND LOCAL FIRE PERSONNEL "DID A GREAT JOB HANDLING TRAFFIC CONTROL.".

THE LEAKING DRUM WAS CLEANED OFF AND IT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL UNTIL THE SHIPPER PROVIDES THE TERMINAL WITH A NEW BUNG.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, A SAFETY-KLEEN EMPLOYEE PUNCTURED A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM WITH THE FORKLIFT. THE PUNCTURED DRUM SPILLED ABOUT 2 GALLONS OF PAINT WASTE INTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO A 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE 55 GALLON POLY DRUM. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 20 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WERE TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 5756 ALBA STREET IN LOS ANGELES, CA FOR TREATMENT/DISPOSAL. THE EMPLOYEE WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER FORKLIFT TECHNIQUE TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

WATKINS MOTOR LINES TRACTOR-TRAILER (TWIN TRAILERS) HEADED WEST ON I40 NEAR SCHOOLTON, OK (MILEPOST 211). IT APPEARS THAT A 65 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM FAILED INSIDE THE REAR TRAILER ALLOWING HYDROCHLORIC ACID TO FLOOD THE ALUMINUM TRAILER FLOOR. THE CHEMICAL REACTION THAT TOOK PLACE WITH THE ACID AND THE ALUMINUM FLOOR ALLOWED THE FORMATION OF HYDROGEN GAS INSIDE THE TRAILER. AT SOME POINT THE HYDROGEN GAS WAS IGNITED CREATING AN EXPLOSION INSIDE THE TRAILER.THE EXPLOSION BLEW THE REAR TRAILER DOOR AND ROOF OUT ALLOWING ACID TO SPILL ONTO THE HIGHWAY. THE EXPLOSION ALSO SPLATTERED FREIGHT THAT WAS LOADED INSIDE THE TRAILER. WE WILL CONTINUE TO WORK WITH THE SHIPPER TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF CONTAINER FAILURE. THIS INCIDENT WAS THE 2ND INCIDENT WITHIN SIXTEEN HOURS INVOLVING THE SAME SHIPMENT. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ONTO A NEW TRAILER ALONG WITH SOME OF THE SAME FREIGHT THAT WAS DAMAGED FROM THE FIRST INCIDENT. WHILE TRANSPORTING THE FREIGHT TO A LOCATION FOR FURTHER DECONTAMINATION, THE SECOND DRUM FAILED ALLOWING ANOTHER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT.

WATKINS MOTOR LINES UNIT (PULLING TWIN TRAILERS) WAS HEADED NORTH ON US HIGHWAY 69 NEAR KIOWA, OK. THE EXPLOSION ALSO SPLATTERED FREIGHT THAT WAS LOADED INSIDE THE TRAILER. WE WILL CONTINUE TO WORK WITH THE SHIPPER TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE CONTAINER FAILURE.

column168: DRESSED IN FULL P.P.E. I WAS CALLED TO A SPILL ON SIDE 6.  I NOTICE DARK RED STAINS ON A PACKAGE MARKED WITH A DOT DIAMOND LABEL- FLAMMABLE LIQUID AND BEARING A DOT 5 - PART LABEL.  I CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE FOLLOWING IT TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET. THE LEAK WAS ISOLATED, THE CONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE DISPOSED OF VIA THE D.M.N. PROCESS.  I FINALLY DECONTAMINATED MY P.P.E.

DRIVER POSITIONED HIS CARGO TANK UNDER LOADING RACK.  HE STARTED HIS PROCEDURE TO LOAD.  AFTER STARTING PUMP, UNIT ROLLED BACKWARDS.  THE MOVEMENT TWISTED THE CATWALK WHICH CAUSED THE DRIVER TO FALL TO THE GROUND.  ALSO THE LOADING HOSE PULLED FROM THE MANHOLE AND RELEASED PRODUCT.  THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PUMP AND THEN WASHED HIMSELF UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER AND THEN NOTIFIED TERMINAL.  OUR TERMINAL PERSONNEL TOOK THE DRIVER TO THE CLINIC TO GET CHECKED OUT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED BY OUR TERMINAL AND SHIPPER PERSONNEL.

A PALLET OF WASTE WAS BEING MOVED WITH A FORKLIFT AT A TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY. A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM FELL OFF OF THE PALLET SPILLING 2 GALLONS INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED 55 GALLON DRUM INTO AN 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 10 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD IN DENTON, TX FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER FORKLIFT TECHNIQUES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

SUBSEQUENT TO RETURNING TO THE OFFICE ALL INVOLVED PERSONNEL AND OTHER LAB PACK PERSONNEL RECEIVED SPECIAL TRAINING ON HOW TO BEST IDENTIFY UNLABELED OR MISLABELED MATERIALS.

A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS AT A 10 DAY STORAGE FACILITY WHEN 3 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION SPILLED OUT OF THE DRUM'S BUNG. THE SPILL OCCURRED IN A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT.  THE MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN AN 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE 55 GALLON DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 30 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 E 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WHO WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE DRUM PICK-UP WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

WHILE UNLOADING THE WASTE OFF OF HIS TRUCK, THE DRIVER KNOCKED OVER A 16 GALLON DRUM OF PETROLEUM NAPHTHA.  THE LID POPPED OFF AND 5 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.   THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND THE MATERIAL CONTAINERIZED.

A TRAILER WAS SITTING ON THE LOT OF A TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY IN ROUTE TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION WHEN THEY FOUND A LEAK COMING OUT OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE LOAD, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM HAD A PINHOLE LEAK AND SPILLED 5 GALLONS OF A SILVER SOLUTION ONTO THE TRAINER FLOOR.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP AND THE 55 GALLON DRUM ALONG WITH WASTE MATERIAL WAS OVERPACKED INTO A 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.

column168: THE PROCEDURE USED TO OFF-LOAD ACID AT THE CHILTON WWTP INVOLVES USING THE VACUUM PUMP THAT IS MOUNTED ON THE TRAILER TO PRESSURIZE THE TANK TO "BLOW OFF" THE LOAD.  THE TANK-MOUNTED PUMPS ARE EQUIPPED WITH A PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE TO PREVENT THE OVER-PRESSURIZATION OF THE TANK.  ALTHOUGH THE RELIEF DEVICES WILL PREVENT THE OVER-PRESSURIZATION OF THE TANK, THE PRESSURE AT WHICH THEY ARE SET OFTEN EXCEEDS THE PRESSURE NEEDED TO OFF-LOAD THE TANK. IN THESE INSTANCES THE DRIVERS HAVE USED A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE TO REDUCE THE PRESSURE ON THE TANK AND SLOW THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS. THE REDUCTION IN THE PRESSURE AND THE SLOWING OF THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS REDUCES THE HAZARDS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS TYPE OF OFF-LOADING PROCEDURE.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SOUTH PHILLY YARD, UTLX 200526 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY VENT. THE CAR WAS SET OUT IN AN ISOLATED AREA AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED. A  REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT THE RUPTURE DISK ON THE CAR HAD BLOWN AND WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO RELEASE WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED. THE SHIPPER'S  REPRESENTATIVE REPLACED THE OLD DISK AND INSPECTED THE CAR FOR OTHER DAMAGE. NO OTHER PROBLEMS WERE DETECTED. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

TANK CAR NATX 37069 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM ITS TOP WHEN MOVED IN MOTION. TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER CALLED. SHIPPER, CONTRACTED YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL TO REPAIR/ FIX CAR. YOUNG'S ARRIVED ON SITE AND FOUND THE LEAK TO BE COMING FROM THE LIQUID LINE NIPPLE DUE TO BEING CROSS THREADED AT THE PRESSURE PLATE. CAR WAS SECURED, READY FOR DESTINATION.

AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN MANWVILLE, NJ, GATX20433, LD HYDROCHLORIC ACID, REPORTED TO BE SMOKING FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED. THE TRAINMASTER REPORTED CAR BELONGS TO THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN (NS) RR. HE CONTRACTED THE LOCAL SUPERINTENDENT FOR THE NS. THE NS DECLINED TO HANDLE THE INCIDENT ACCOUNT THE CAR WAS IN CSXT'S PORTION OF MANVILLE YD. CSXT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO MAKE REPAIRS. THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THE CAR HAD A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK. THE BLOWN DISK WS A 100 LB DISK ( THE CAR WAS STENCILED FOR A 165 LB DISK). THEY REPLACED THE BLOWN DISK WITH A 165 LB DISK. THE CAR WAS SECURED & RELEASED.

AT CSC TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN MONTGOMERY, AL, ULTX203196, LD ACETONE, WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN IT IS SITTING STILL. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER RESPONDED A TEAM FROM THEIR BURKEVILLE, AL PLANT TO REPAIR CAR. THE SHIPPER RESPONDED A TEAM FROM THEIR BURKEVILLE, AL PLANT TO REPAIR CAR. THE SHIPPER FOUND CAR WAS PRESSURIZED & WAS LEAKING WHERE THE LIQUID LOADING VALVE ASSEMBLY NIPPLE SCREWS INTO THE TOP OF THE TANK. THEY RELIEVED THE PRESSURE AND TIGHTENED THE VALVE INTO THE TOP OF THE TANK. THE LEAK WAS STOPPED & THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

CHTT 286790, LOADED GONDOLA ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE ( FERROUS SULFATE) WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING LIQUID AT THE CAR SHOP IN CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN RIVERDALE, IL.. THE CAR DEPARTMENT REPORTED A GREEN "LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE CORNER OF CAR & CREATED A PUDDLE IN THE TRACK.THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED. CSXT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO CLEANUP THE SPILL & INSPECT THE CAR. THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THE TARP ON CAR WAS PULLED AWAY FROM BOTH ENDS & THE RIGHT SIDE ALLOWING RAIN WATER TO ENTER CAR. THE CAR IS NOT LINED.THEY PULLED THE TARP BACK OVER THE CAR & PLACED BUCKETS UNDER THE LEAKS AT THE BOTTOM EDGES OF THE CAR. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SOLIDIFIED WITH BAKING SODA, AND PLACED IN 55 GAL DRUMS. THE CONTRACTOR ATTEMPTED TO PATCH AREAS WHERE CAR RUSTED & LEAKING BUT THE PUTTY WOULD NOT STICK. SPOKE TO A REP FROM THE SHIPPER, THEY SENT REP TO INSPECT CAR & DETERMINED CAR MUST BE TRANSLOADED. THE SHIPPER WORKING WITH CSXT DIVERSIONS TO GET EMPTY CAR TO YARD FOR A TRANSFER.
column172: Rail hopper car for solid materials only

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT CUMBERLAND TERMINAL, APHX 2014, WAS FOUND TO BE VENTING A MIXTURE OF LIQUID (DROPLETS) AND VAPOR FORM THE SAFETY VENT PIPE. SWITCHING ACTIVITIES AND TRAIN TRAFFIC WERE SUSPENDED IN THE YARD AND THE IMMEDIATE AREA AROUND THE LEAKING CAR WAS ISOLATED. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT THE LIQUID LINE VALVE (V-1) WAS PARTIALLY OPEN, AND REQUIRED A 1/4 TO 1/2 TURN TO FULLY CLOSE THE VALVE. UPON CLOSING VALVE V-1, THE VENTING WAS SIGNIFICANTLY DECREASED. THE HAZMAT TEAM ALSO FOUND THAT THE MANUAL RELIEF VALVE (V-9) WAS PARTIALLY OPEN AND REQUIRED A 1/4 TURN TO FULLY CLOSE THE VALVE. AFTER CLOSING THE V-9 VALVE, THE VENTING STOPPED AND NO FURTHER RELEASE WAS DETECTED. BOTH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND AN INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR CHECKED THE AREA AROUND THE CAR FOR FLAMMABLE VAPORS. NO VAPORS WERE DETECTED AND NORMAL OPERATIONS WERE ALLOWED TO RESUME.

column168: AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN WILLARD, OH, WHILE SWITCHING AN EMPTY HOPPER CAR, NAHX 516183, STRUCK MHFX 5241 & ITS KNUCKLE PUNCHED A HOLE INTO THE END OF THE MHFX 5241. THE MHFX CAR IS LOADED WITH INNER CONTAINERS OF RADIOACTIVE (LSA) SOILS. INITIAL REPORTS INDICATED NONE OF INNER CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED. ON 8/14, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 2 OF THE INNER BAGS IN THE GON WERE TORN & DIRT INSIDE WAS EXPOSED. THIS INFORMATION WAS RELAYED TO THE SHIPPER. THEY RESPONDED PEOPLE TO INSPECT BAGS & SURVEY AREA. CSXT RESPONDED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MGR TO THE YARD. THE SHIPPER REP ON SCENE REPORTED SOME OF THE DIRT HAD BEEN PULLED OUT OF THE CAR ON THE COUPLER OF THE COVERED HOPPER THEY ISOLATED AREA AROUND CAR & AREA WHERE ACCIDENT OCCURRED. THEY SURVEYED AREAS & DETECTED NO EVIDENCE OF ANY RADIOACTIVITY. HE CONFIRMED NO DIRT FROM THE GON WAS SPILLED ON THE GROUND. ON 08/15/00, A CRANE WAS USED TO REMOVE THE DAMAGED BAGS AND OVERPACKED THEM. THE END SHEET OF THE CAR WAS REPAIRED & THE OVERPACKED BAGS WERE LOADED BACK INTO THE CAR. ON 08/16/00 THE SHIPPER REP REPORTED THEY WERE ALL FINISHED AND THE CAR HAD BEEN OK'D TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

WHEN UNLOADING TRAILER, DOCKWORKER FOUND THIS CONTAINER CRUSHED AND SLIGHTLY LEAKING AT BOTTOM OF CONTAINER.  I AM GOING TO ASSUME THAT IT WAS NOT BRACED PROPERLY AND I AM NOT SURE WHAT CONTRIBUTED TO THIS FAILURE.  DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY:           ELDREDGE INC 898 FERNHILL ROAD WEST CHESTER, PA 19382

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, THERE WAS A DRUM WITH LIQUID AROUND IT. WHEN DRUM WAS REMOVED IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS A NAIL IN THE TRAILER FLOOR THAT HAD PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND SHIPPED TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND ABSORBENT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINERS. TRAILER FLOORS NEED TO BE CHECKED BETTER IN FUTURE FOR NAILS AND OTHER OBJECTS THAT MIGHT DAMAGE PRODUCTS.

LEAKING BOTTLE WAS REMOVED FROM BOX AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AS PER INSTRUCTED.

column168: NOTE:  NO PACKAGING FAILURE OCCURRED.  GW INTERNATIONAL DRIVER NOTED BULGED HYDROGEN PEROXIDE DRUM IN TRUCK WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY. SANTA ROSA FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED BY EVACUATING 500 FT AROUND VEHICLE.  THE DRUM WAS VENTED BY USING A REMOTE DRUM PUNCTURING MACHINE.  NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE RELEASED ON THE VEHICLE.  THE DRUM WAS THEN MOVED TO A SAFE, CONTAINED AREA WHERE THE REACTION THAT CAUSED THE BULGING ACCELERATED AND PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE NEW OPEN BUNGS IN THE DRUM WATER WAS APPLIED TO DILUTE THE SPILL AND SPILLED MATERIAL WAS PUMPED TO A SAFE WASTE WATER TANK. CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FOR THE INCIDENT INCLUDE STEPS TO BE TAKEN AT GWI, WHERE THE DRUM WAS FILLED.  SINCE THE SUSPECTED CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT/REACTION WAS TRACE METAL CONTAMINATION IN THE DRUM, THE FOLLOWING CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WERE TAKEN:
DRIVER AIR LINE DAMAGED WENT TO DISCONNECT HOSE AND LOST PRODUCT. CUSTOMER CLEANING UP SPILL.
DRIVER UNLOADING INTO CUSTOMER TANK CUSTOMER TANK OVERFLOWED. CUSTOMER USED SPILL PADS TO CLEAN UP SPILL.
CUSTOMER LAID OUT DEDICATED HOSE FOR DRIVER.  PRODUCT CAME OUT WHEN DRIVER REMOVED CAP.  USED  SPILL PADS TO CLEAN UP.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: CUSTOMER HAD JUST FINISHED UPGRADING THEIR TANK AND THE MAN HOLE ON SIDE OF TANK WAS LEAKING.

PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AS DRIVER WAS IN PROCESS OF COLLECTING A SAMPLER FROM THE CARGO TANK OUTLET.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED BECAUSE THE DRIVER FIRST OPENED THE CARGO TANK'S EXTERNAL VALVE AND THEN THE INTERNAL VALVE.  THIS ACTION RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF A GREATER VOLUME OF PRODUCT THAN ANTICIPATED.  CLEAN UP WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL.

column168: APPEARS THAT OUR VEHICLE DRIFTED OVER TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER AND THEN HIT THE GUARDRAIL.  AFTER HITTING THE GUARDRAIL, OUR TRUCK HIT THE LEFT SIDE BARRIER WHILE GOING OVER A BRIDGE.  THIS THEN RESULTED IN THE TRAILER BEING SPLIT IN HALF.  ONE HALF STAYED CONNECTED TO THE TRACTOR, AND THE OTHER HALF WENT OVER THE BRIDGE AND INTO THE CREEK BELOW THE BRIDGE.  ALL LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED AND CLEAN UP WAS STARTED.  CLEAN UP IS STILL CONTINUING.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT THE TRUCK PULLED SUDDENLY TO THE RIGHT PRIOR TO IMPACT, BUT AS OF TODAY NOTHING MECHANICALLY WRONG WITH THE TRUCK HAS BEEN DISCOVERED.

column168: DRIVER ENROUTE, STOPPED AT DART FACILITY IN CANFIELD, OHIO.  WHILE AT TERMINAL DRIVER CHECKED HIS LOAD AND NOTICED THE FLOOR WAS WET. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  CLEAN HARBORS ENV. SERVICES WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION.  DRUM WAS LOCATED, OVERPACKED, TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP AND DRIVER WAS ABLE TO PROCEED.

column168: DRIVER LOST CONTROL, LEFT THE HIGHWAY AND OVERTURNED.  TANK TRAILER WAS CRUSHED IN CAUSING A LEAK IN ONE COMPARTMENT SPILLING APPROX. 2999 GALLONS.  HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED FROM ABOUT 9:00 AM TO 6:30 PM NORTHBOUND.  ABOUT 10 HOMES WERE EVACUATED FOR THE SAME TIME. DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO LOCAL HOSPITAL DUE TO INJURIES SUSTAINED IN THE VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES IN DECATUR.  AL WERE CONTRACTED FOR CLEANUP.

THE SHIPPER HAD ADVISED US THAT THE PRODUCT WAS NOT A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND WAS NOT REGULATED, AND IT WAS TRANSPORTED AS A NON REGULATED PRODUCT.  WE DIDN'T KNOW THAT IT WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL UNTIL DAYS AFTER THE ACCIDENT

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING SIX, ONE QUART PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WAS DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING FIVE WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY A HALF A QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND ABSORBED BY THE CARTON.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE DURING LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND WET CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WAS TAPED UP, REPACKAGED WITH THE REMAINING FIVE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES AND FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY SIX GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGE FAILURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO FOUR, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED TWENTY FIVE GALLON PLASTIC BAG WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY A HALF CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE BAG WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION, A DUSTPAN AND A BROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED BAG WAS TAPED UP AND FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column42: HYDRAZINE, AQUEOUS SOLUTION, WITH NOT MORE THAN 37 PERCENT HYDRAZINE, BY MASS
column168: WHILE LOADING, A LEAKING 350-GALLON STEEL TOTE TANK WAS DISCOVERED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE TOTE TANK WAS LEAKING DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL B.  ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO SIX, TEN-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS.  THE FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE LEAKING TOTE TANK WAS WIPED OFF, AND WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER'S DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING 55-GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY THREE OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT NEUTRALIZERS.  THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 5-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE BUNG ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DRUM WAS THE ONLY PIECE IN THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE-GALLON GLASS CONTAINERS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED AND TWO WERE AFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINERS WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND TWO DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE-GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TWO AFFECTED CONTAINERS WERE CLEANED OFF,REPACKAGED AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE ON THE DOCK, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED ONE LEAKING, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM.  APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENTS AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE BUNG ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND IT WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, SIXTEEN, 5-GALLON CONTAINERS WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE CLOSURE ON EACH OF THE CONTAINERS. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 55-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE CLOSURE ON EACH OF THE SIXTEEN CONTAINERS WERE SECURED AND THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING TWO, ONE QUART CYLINDERS AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE CYLINDER WAS DAMAGED AND THE OTHER WAS AFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND ABSORBED BY THE CARTON. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGE FAILURE.  H.M.H.T.T.C. OF POMONA, CA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  H.M.H.T.T.C. PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL B PROTECTION.  H.M.H.T.T.C. PLACED THE WET CARTON AND THE TWO CYLINDERS INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM.  THEY THEN PLACED THE DRUM INTO A EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON OVERPACK.  THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THERE IS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  THERE WERE SIX ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. EMPLOYEES EXPOSED TO THE RELEASE.  FOUR OF THE EXPOSED EMPLOYEES RECEIVED MEDICAL ATTENTION FROM A LOCAL MEDICAL FACILITY.  TWO OF THE EXPOSED EMPLOYEES DID NOT REQUIRE MEDICAL ATTENTION.  NO HOSPITALIZATION WAS REQUIRED FOR ANY OF THE EXPOSURES.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS SEALED WITH PUTTY AND PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 55- GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

SERVICES WAS NOTIFIED AND PROCEEDED TO SEND A CREW FROM FERGUSON HARBORS TO RESPOND TO THE PROBLEM. AFTER ASSESSING THE SITUATION FERGUSON HARBORS DETERMINED THE TOTE HAD STOPPED LEAKING AND CLEANED UP AREA AROUND TOTE. DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CONTINUE ON. AT 7:10 AM ON AUGUST 5, 2000 OUR DRIVER NOTIFIED SAFETY DEPT. THAT THE TOTE WAS LEAKING ONCE AGAIN. DART ONCE AGAIN NOTIFIED CLEAN HARBORS ENV. SERVICES OF THE SITUATION. CLEAN HARBORS SENT OUT A CREW TO MEET DRIVER AT SPRING GROVE FACILITY AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD TRAILER AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED ONTO FLOOR.
DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE REAR DOOR OF TRAILER.  BUCKET WAS THROWN FROM THE TRAILER WHILE ROUNDING A CORNER.  BUCKET LANDED ON PAVEMENT AND THE LID BURST OFF.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: ON AUGUST 23, 2000 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:10AM OUR DRIVER CALLED TO REPORT HE HAD 35% HYDROGEN PEROXIDE LEAKING FROM A BARREL ON HIS TRUCK.  WE HAD HIM CONTACT THE LOCAL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM IN HENRICO COUNTY IMMEDIATELY. OUR PERSONNEL DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE WITH ADDITIONAL MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOKS AND CHEMICAL DICTIONARIES.  ULTIMATELY IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO WASH THE SPILLED MATERIAL INTO A NEARBY SEWER. THE MANUFACTURER OF THE MATERIAL SAID IT WOULD BE HARMLESS IF DILUTED.  ALL ACTIONS TAKEN WERE UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE COUNTY OF HENRICO, THE VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY SERVICES AND THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY. AFTER THE INITIAL INVESTIGATION WE BELIEVE THE DRUM FAILED WITHOUT CAUSE(SEE ATTACHED PHOTOGRAPH).  THERE IS NO EXTERNAL DAMAGE TO THE DRUM. IT WAS ON A PLASTIC  PALLET AND WAS BRACED WITH A STRAP TO THE SIDE OF THE TRUCK (SEE DIAGRAM).  THERE WERE NO PROTRUSIONS ON THE SIDE OF THE VEHICLE THAT COULD HAVE PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  WE OBTAINED AN OPINION FROM A LOCAL DRUM RECONDITIONER AND THEIR BELIEF WAS ALSO DRUM FAILURE. WE HAVE CONTACTED THE DRUM MANUFACTURER TO ASK FOR ASSISTANCE IN DETERMINING THE PROBLEM.  WE HOPE TO OBTAIN THEIR AID IN PREVENTING FUTURE PROBLEMS, AS IT WAS CLEARLY A DRUM QUALITY ISSUE.  THE INVESTIGATION IS ONGOING AT THIS TIME.

ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE SPILLAGE WAS ABSORBED AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER. THE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE-GALLON METAL PAILS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FIRST QUARTERMARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE PAIL WAS DAMAGED AND NONE WERE AFFECTED.APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE CARTON AND ADJACENT DUNNAGE. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PPE AND ABSORBENT PADS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE DAMAGED PAIL AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE CARTON WAS CLEANED OFF AND FORWARDED, WITH THREE UNAFFECTED PAILS, ON TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE 55-GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT NEUTRALIZER. THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 14 -GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE BUNG ON THE LEAKING DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE DRUM WAS THE ONLY PIECE IN THE SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE LOADING, FOUR LEAKING 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE LEAKAGE WAS CAUSED BY LOOSE DRUM VENT CAPS. THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING AMPHOMAG ABSORBENT NEUTRALIZER. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 5 GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION AT THE TERMINAL. THE DRUM VENT CAPS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE DRUMS CONTINUED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING, A DAMAGED 220 POUND FIBERBOARD BOX WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE STAPLES ON THE BOTTOM CLOSURE FAILED. THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM SWEPT UP THE FREE PRODUCT USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND PLACED IT INTO A 35 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE DAMAGED SHIPPING CONTAINER. THE RECOVERY DRUM  WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 5 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE LOADING, ONE DAMAGED 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE 1/2 WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 2 CUPS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE STEEL DRUM WAS THE RESULT OF A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM. THE DAMAGED 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM AND CONTENTS WERE PLACED INTO A 80 GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM. BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGE 50 POUND PLASTIC BAG WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 6 OUNCE OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE BAG WAS TORN IN TRANSIT BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM SWEPT UP THE FREE PRODUCT USING LEVEL C PROTECTION. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 50 GALLON AND A 10 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION AT THE TERMINAL. THE FREE PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO A 50 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT. THE DAMAGED BAG WAS RE-BAGGED AND WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. ONE EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO THE FREE PRODUCT, BUT RETURNED TO WORK AFTER RINSING. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, 1 -GALLON CONTAINERS WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING AND THREE WERE AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE.THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS, FOUR DAMAGED CONTAINERS, AND THE AFFECTED CARTON WERE PLACED INTO AN 85-GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE PAIL WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO TWO 55 GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS AND TWO 85 GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS. THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DAMAGED DRUM WILL BE WIPED OFF AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. WHILE UNLOADING, TWO DAMAGED, 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FORTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUMS WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ONE BOX OF DYKES, AMPHOMAG ABSORBENTS, ABSORBENT PADS, A SHOVEL, A BROOM, AND A DUSTPAN. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO TWO 45 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS. THE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

A TANK CAR HAD BEEN LOADED WITH WASTE OIL CONTAINING 3 PPM POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENYL (PCB). THE CAR WAS OVER-FILLED BY NOT LEAVING ENOUGH ROOM FOR EXPANSION. THE TANKER CAR HEATED UP DURING THE DAY AND 15 GALLON SPILLED OUT OF THE TOP OF THE CAR INTO A SPILL PAN AND 5 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE GRAVEL BELOW. THE MATERIAL WAS PUMPED OUT OF THE SPILL PAN INTO METAL DRUMS AND THE SPILL PAN CLEANED OUT. THE CONTAMINATED GRAVEL WAS ALSO CONTAINERIZED. ADDITIONAL MATERIAL WAS PUMPED OUT OF THE TANK CAR TO ALLOW FOR EXPANSION. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 1,448 KILOGRAMS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 11600 NORTH APTUS ROAD IN ARAGONITE, UT FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL AND THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL WAS SENT TO 2027 BATTLEGROUND ROAD IN DEER PARK, TX  FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE EMPLOYEES WERE COUNSELED ON CHECKING OF PROPER HEAD SPACE WHEN FILLING A TANKER TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: DURING TRANSPORTATION TO ITS FINAL DESIGNATED FACILITY, A DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY OTHER ON THE TRAILER AND SPILLED 1 PINT OF PAINT ONTO THE FLOOR. THE SPILL WAS NOT DISCOVERED UNTIL THE NEXT DAY. WHEN THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED, IT WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 3 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TREATED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, AT THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 16540 SE 130TH AVE BLDG B IN CLACKAMAS, OR. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM LOADING AND SECUREMENT PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

AS THIS SHIPMENT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED FROM BREAKDOWN TO BUILD-UP, ONE PIECE FELL FROM THE WOODEN SKID UPON WHICH IT WAS PLACED. THE PIECE WAS THEN RUN OVER BY THE TRANSPORTING FORKLIFT. THE BOX WAS DAMAGED, AS WERE SEVERAL OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS. THE DAMAGED PIECE WAS HELD FOR DISPOSAL.
THIS CARTON WAS EATEN AWAY BY THE SOLUTION. NO OTHER FREIGHT DAMAGED. THIS OCCURED WHILE LOADING DRIVER CDY UNIT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Overfilled
column168: PRODUCT WAS LOADED BY SHIPPER. UNIT WAS WEIGHED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THE GROSS WEIGHT EXCEEDED THE CORRECT AMOUNT OF WEIGHT. SHIPPER'S EMPLOYEE PREPARED HOSES AND VALVES TO OFF LOAD THE EXTRA PRODUCT INTO EMPTY TANK. DRIVER OPENED VALVE TO OFF LOAD AND SOME PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF VALVE. SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND NO FURTHER ASSISTANCE WAS REQUIRED. TWO OF THE SHIPPER'S EMPLOYEES PREPARED TO BLEED THE PRESSURE OFF OF THE PRESSURE LINE/HOSE AND ASKED DRIVER TO LEAVE LOADING/ UNLOADING AREA. SHIPPER ATTEMPTED TO EASE OFF PRESSURE BY REMOVING THE FITTING FROM THE TRAILER BUT THE PRESSURE PUSHED THE CAP OFF OF TRAILER AND SPRAYED PRODUCT ONTO SHIPPER'S EMPLOYEE. THE SHIPPER'S EMPLOYEE WAS WEARING A CHEMICAL SUIT, HOWEVER, CHEMICAL WAS SPRAYED ONTO FACIAL AND BACK AREAS. SHIPPER SHOWERED OFF IN SAFETY SHOWER AND TAKEN TO HOSPITAL. EMPLOYEE WAS RELEASED FROM THE EMERGENCY ROOM AND RETURNED TO WORK THE FOLLOWING DAY. SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED. THE REMAINING PRESSURE AND PRODUCT WERE EMPTIED FROM PRESSURE LINE INTO DRIP BUCKET BY ANOTHER EMPLOYEE OF SHIPPER. THE EXTRA PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT. NO ASSISTANCE REQUIRED.

column168: PALLET WAS MARKED AS HAZMAT, BUT NO BLOCKING OR BRACING WAS USED. DURING SHIPMENT, PALLET IN FRONT OF SHIPMENT SHIFTED AND PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE PAILS, CAUSING IT TO LEAK FOR THE DURATION OF THE LINERUN. THE DEFECTIVE PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY PAIL, ALONG WITH THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS, AND THEN PLACED IN OS & D. THIS COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED BY PROPER USE OF DUNNAGE AROUND THE HAZMAT PALLET, AND PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING OF SURROUNDING PALLET.

column168: UTLX 11022 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP IN CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN INDAINAPOLIS, IN.  PRODUCT SPLASHED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR ON TO A CSXT EMPLOYEE'S SHIRT.  THE PRODUCT DID NOT COME IN CONTACT WITH HIS SKIN.  THE EMPLOYEE REMOVED HIS SHIRT AND WAS NOT INJURED. THE CONSIGNEE RESPONDED PERSONNEL AND DETERMINED THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TANK NOZZLE GASKET.  THE CONSIGNEE MADE TEMPORARY REPAIRS TO STOP THE LEAK AND THE CAR WAS MOVED INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY FOR UNLOADING AND PERMANENT REPAIRS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON AUGUST 27, 2000, CSXT PERSONNEL IN THE TILFORD YARD IN ATLANTA, GA, REPORTED ACFX 88194, A LOADED TANK CAR OF ACETONE, LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND BUCKETS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK. A CSXT CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE LOOSE.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE CONTRACTOR CLEANED THE SPILL AREA AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON AUGUST 26, 2000, CSXT PERSONNEL IN THE DANVILLE, IL RAIL YARD REPORTED AN ODOR FROM ACFX 12055.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A CSXT CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE YARD.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND SIX MANWAY BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, THE ODOR ABATED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.

TANK CAR GATX 6866 WAS BEING FLAT SWITCHED AT THE NEEDMORE YARD IN DAYTON, OH.  THE BRAKEMAN WAS GOING TO PULL THE PIN ON THIS PARTICULAR CAR AFTER GIVING A KICK TO THE PREVIOUS CAR.  WHEN HE WENT TO PULL THE PIN THE PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT THE TOP AND ON TO THE BRAKEMAN.  BRAKEMAN RAN INTO AND SHOWERED OFF.  WAS TAKEN TO LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION AND RELEASED.  BRAKEMAN RETURNED BACK TO WORK.  NEXT DAY OR TWO HE MARKED OFF "PERSONAL BUSINESS", THEN MARKED OFF DUE TO INJURY.  CSX MANAGER OF HAZMAT RESPONDED AND INVESTIGATED WITH SHIPPER (MARSULEX).  BOTH FOUND THE FOLLOWING: THE SAFETY VENT (SALCO PRODUCTS SAFETY VENT) HAD THE SURGE BASKET, DISC COLLAR AND CAP MISSING.  THE COLLAR AND CAP HAVE A SMALL CABLE LIKE TIE.  THESE "TIE" TO THE MAIN VENT PIECE ON TOP ON THE TANK. THESE APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN "TORN" AWAY FROM THERE CABLE TIE. SHIPPER RESPONDED WITH A NEW ASSEMBLY.  CAR WAS REPAIRED BY REPLACING MISSING PIECES OF THE ASSEMBLY.  TANK CAR MOVED ON TO DESTINATION.

ON AUGUST 30, 2000, CSXT PERSONNEL IN ATLANTA, GA OBSERVED UTLX 8011632, A LOADED TANK CAR OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION, LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE SAFETY VENT OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND A CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE RUPTURE DISC BLOWN AND PRODUCT ON THE TOP AND SIDE OF THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR CHANGED THE RUPTURE DISC AND DECONTAMINATED THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE CAR HAD A LEVEL ABOVE THE 2% OUTAGE MARKER.  A REVIEW OF THE SCALE WEIGHTS IN TRANSIT AND AT THE SHIPPER'S LOADING FACILITY SHOWED THE CAR AT AN APPROPRIATE WEIGHT. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.

THIS TANK CAR HAD LIQUID SHOWING ON ITS SIDES.  NO FITTINGS WERE LOOSE.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED.  THE SHIPPER HIRED A REPAIR COMPANY TO CHECK THE CAR AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  THE FITTINGS NOZZLE FLANGE GASKET WAS REPAIRED.  MANIFEST IS NOT AVAILABLE TO THE PREPARER OF THIS DOCUMENT; HOWEVER THE NUMBERS ARE: 8035677-8035678-8035679 AND 8035676.

GATX 61156 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK AT THE CSXT TRANSFER YARD, INDIANAPOLIS, IN.  THE DRIP LEAK WAS OBSERVED TO BE COMING FROM THE SUMP AREA ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THE CONSIGNEE RESPONDED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE CAR HAD A POSSIBLE LINER FAILURE THAT RESULTED IN CORROSION TO THE TANK SHELL.  THE CONSIGNEE TRANSLOADED THE PRODUCT INTO TANKER TRUNKS FOR DELIVERY.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CAPTURED IN A CATCH PAN PLACED UNDER THE CAR.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER WAS ON SCENE TO PROVIDE OVERSIGHT FOR THE TRANSFER OPERATION.

DURING TANK CAR INSPECTION, THIS TANK CAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE A SLIP-TUBE GAUGING DEVICE WITH A LOOSE PACKING NUT.  APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TURN WAS APPLIED TO THE PACKING NUT, AND THERE WAS NO FURTHER EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE. TISI = 40
DRIVER WAS AIRING OFF PRODUCT WHEN 3" HOSE FAILED AND RELEASED 20 - 30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON CONCRETE PAD.  UNLOADING WAS STOPPED IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING RUPTURE.

APPROXIMATELY 60 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DRUMS WERE PUNCTURED IN TRANSIT BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. RINCHEM COMPANY OF EL PASO, TX WAS DISPATCHED BY THE RAILROAD TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP. ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT. THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS AND THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO THREE 65 GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUMS. THE OVERPACK DRUMS REMAINED IN THE TRAILER AND CONTINUED ON TO THE TERMINAL WITH THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT. NO SOIL OR WATER WAS AFFECTED. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE LOADING, ONE 55-GALLON DRUM WAS DAMAGED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE. CACTUS ENVIRONMENTAL OF DALLAS, TEXAS RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN-UP. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, EIGHT BAGS WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BAGS WERE APPARENTLY LEAKING AT THE SEAMS. APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE CAUSE OF THE LEAKING BAG WAS DUE TO PACKAGING FAILURE. CACTUS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, OF DALLAS, TEXAS, PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING A GRANULAR ABSORBENT, BROOM AND DUSTPAN. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS ALONG WITH TWO OF THE LEAKING BAGS WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM AND LEFT AT THE TERMINAL FOR  DISPOSITION. THE REMAINING SIX BAGS WILL BE FORWARDED, ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT, TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING,ONE DAMAGED, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING BAKING SODA, WATER AND GLOVES. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: DRIVER STOPPED FOR A BREAK AND TO CHECK HIS LOAD PRIOR TO BEGINNING MAKIING HIS DELIVERIES. WHEN HE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR HE SAW LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WHICH WAS FUMING SLIGHTLY. HE WAS ABLE TO IDENTIFY IT AS COMING FROM THE MANWAY COVER OF AN I B C THAT WAS LOCATED NEAR THE TRAIL END OF THE TRAILER. THERE WAS NO ESCAPE OF PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER. SINCE HE WAS QUITE CLOSE A FACILITY OF THE CARRIER'S ON-DUTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN AGREED TO HAVE HIM PUT DOWN SPILL PADS ON THE STANDING LIQUID AND PUT AN ABSORBENT BOOM ACROSS THE TRAILER DOOR, THEN PROCEED TO THE FACILITY. ON ARRIVAL AT THE FACILITY, DOCK PERSONNEL FAMILIAR WITH THE PRODUCT INSPECTED THE I B C AND SAW THAT ITS MANWAY COVER RING CLAMP WAS LOOSE. DOCK PERSONNEL PLACED SPEEDY DRY ON THE LIQUID IN THE TRAILER AND PROCEEDED TO OFF-LOAD THE LEAKING PACKAGE. BOTH PACKAGES FROM THIS SHIPMENT WERE PULLED FROM THE TRAILER AND PLACED IN A VENITLLATED AREA IN THE WAREHOUSE. THE REMAINDER OF THE FREIGHT IN THE TRAILER WAS RE-LOADED ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR DELIVERY. THE CARRIER'S TECHNICIAN SPOKE WITH A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER REGARDING THE INCIDENT AND REPAIR OF THE LEAKING I B C. THE SHIPPER'S REPRESENTATIVE INDICATED THAT THE LOGISTICS COMPANY WHO FILLS THE PACKAGES FOR WILL SEND PERSONNEL TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY TO FIX THE LEAK ON THE I B C(S), THEN CLEAN THEM UP FOR SHIPMENT AND CLEAN ANY RESIDUE LEFT IN THE TRAILER. ANY SPILL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL CAN BE SENT WITH THEM FOR DISPOSAL. THE TRAILER THAT HAD TRANSPORTED THE I B C's  IN WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE. THE SHIPPER MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE IT DECONTAMINATED.

DURING UNLOADING OF AN INBOUND TRAILER AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY, ONE DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM AROUND ITS BUNG. THE SPILLAGE WAS CONFINED TO THE DRUM'S HEAD. CARRIER DOCK PERSONNEL PUT ABSORBENT ON THE SPILLAGE AND OVERPACKED THE DRUM. AT THE REQUEST OF THE SHIPPER IT WAS DELIVERED. NO FURTHER INCIDENT ENSUED.

AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP THE DRIVER ENCOUNTERED A STRONG ODOR IN THE TRAILER. HE FOUND ONE PAIL THAT HAD BEEN CREASED, POSSIBLY BY A FORK BLADE. THE CREASE DEVELOPED A LEAK AT ITS APEX. IT WAS DRIBBLING VERY SLOWLY. DRIVER PLACED SPILL PADS UNDER IT AND A SOCK AROUND IT. HE THEN ACQUIRED ANOTHER PAIL TO SET THE LEAKER INTO. HE HAS IT SECURED IN THE TRAILER FOR RETURN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY.

THEY DID TIGHTEN THE CAP AND PLACE THE DRUM INTO A PLASTIC BAG. THE DRIVER RETURNED IT TO THE CARRIER'S LOCAL FACILITY TO BE HELD FOR INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHEN THE CONSIGNEE OPENED FOR BUSINESS, THE DRIVER BEGAN TO OPEN THE TRAILER'S OVERHEAD DOOR. SEEING A LARGE QUANTITY OF INK STARTING TO RUN FROM THE TRAILER, HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE DOOR, NOTIFIED THE CONSIGNEE AND MOVED THE UNIT TO LEVEL GROUND. CONSIGNEE'S DOCK PERSON THEN NOTIFIED SUN CHEMICAL PERSONNEL WHO WORK AT THE FACILITY. SUN PERSONNEL MADE ENTRY AND CONTOLLED THE SPILL, THE HAD THE DRIVER MOVE THE TRAILER INTO THE DOCK. column168: DURING UNLOADING OF DEWARS OF CRYOGENIC HELIUM AT THE CARRIER'S DELIVERING FACILITY, ONE DEWAR WAS KNOCKED OVER AND BEGAN LEAKING FROM A VALVE. THE TRAILER WAS MOVED AWAY FROM THE DOCK AND INTO A REMOTE AREA OF THE YARD. THE CARRIER'S DUTY HAZMAT TECHNICIAN WAS CALLED FOR DIRECTION. THE TECHNICIAN INSTRUCTED FACILITY PERSONNEL TO STAY AWAY FROM TRAILER UNTIL THE CLOUD CLEARED AND THE CYLINDER WAS NO LONGER LEAKING. WHEN THE LEAKAGE HAD STOPPED AND THE TRAILER WAS VENTED, IT WAS RETURNED BACK INTO THE DOCK, AND UNLOADING WAS COMPLETED. THE HAZMAT TECHNICIAN INTERVIEWED THE UNLOADER OF THE TRAILER. HE STATED THAT WHEN HE UNLOADED THE DEWERS THEY WERE EACH STRAPPED TO BOTH SIDES OF THE WALL, AND BRACED IN WITH LOGISTIC BARS IN THE FRONT AND BACK OF THE  CYLINDERS. HE STATED THAT THERE WAS SHRINK WRAP TIED AROUND THE PRODUCT VALVE AND THE SHRINK WRAP WAS ALSO TIED TO THE LOGISTIC BAR. WHEN HE REMOVED THE LOGISTIC BAR THAT WAS TOWARD THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER, THE DEWER FELL OVER. THE LOADER OF THE TRAILER AT THE ORIGINATING FACILITY STATED THAT WHEN THE CYLINDER WAS LOADED IT HAD A LOOSE VALVE ON IT SO HE TIED SHRINK WRAP AROUND IT TO KEEP IT FROM OPENING IN TRANSIT TO THE DELIVERING FACILITY. DOCK PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN REMINDED THAT DEWARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH PRODUCT VALVES AND RELIEF VALVE. RELIEF VALVES MAY VENT AND GIVE THE APPEARANCE OF LEAKING. ANY UNRECOGNIZED LEAKAGE SHOULD BE REPORTED IMMEDIATELY. IT IS NEVER ACCEPTABLE PRACTICE TO "TIE DOWN" A VALVE OR TO USE ONE AS A POINT OF SECUREMENT.

column168: HAZMAT RECEIVED A CALL FROM A DRIVER WHO WAS AT ANOTHER FACILITY OF THE CARRIER. EARLIER IN THE DAY HAD GOTTEN SOME H/M ON HIS SHIRT (CHEST AND STOMACH). HE HAD BEEN HELPING A CONSIGNEE REMOVE THEIR FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER. A BAG HAD BEEN TORN DURING THE UNLOADING AND THE CHEMICAL, A POWDER, SPILLED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE POWDER WAS NOT IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP AND THE CONSIGNEE'S FORK LIFT KEPT RUNNING THROUGH IT. THE DRIVER WAS USING A PALLET JACK TO HELP THE CONSIGNEE MOVE THE FREIGHT AND HE HAD TO LIFT THE PALLET JACK UP FROM THE REAR TO GET IT UNDER THE PALLET. AT THE TIME HE LIFTED THE UP JACK, ITS WHEELS WERE CONTAMINATED WITH THE POWDER. THE WHEELS TOUCHED HIS SHIRT, TRANSFERRING SOME POWDER TO THE SHIRT. THE DRIVER DID NOT IMMEDIATELY WASH OR REMOVE HIS SHIRT, BUT CONTINUED BACK TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY. WHEN HE ARRIVED THERE HE NOTICED A BURNING SENSATION AND WENT INTO THE REST ROOM TO WASH UP. AS HE ADDED WATER TO THE PRODUCT ON HIS CHEST HE STATED THE BURNING SENSATION BECAME INCREASINGLY WORSE. AT THIS TIME HE CALLED THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN FOR DIRECTION. THE TECHNICIAN NOTIFIED CHEM TREC FOR AN MSDS. CHEMTREC IN TURN NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER. THE CARRIER'S TECHNICIAN FORWARDED THE MSDS TO THE LOCAL FACILITY. HE DIRECTED FACILITY MANAGEMENT TO HAVE THE DRIVER TAKEN A HOSPITAL ACCOMPANIED BY THE MSDS. DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO MORRISTOWN MEMORIAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE RECEIVED APPROPRIATE TREATMENT AND WAS RELEASED IN GOOD CONDITION SEVERAL HOURS LATER WITH INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE HOSPITAL FOR FOLLOW UP CARE. THE PRODUCT REACTS WITH SMALL AMOUNTS OF WATER AND MUST BE GENEROUSLY FLUSHED. THE DRIVER HAS SUFFERED NO ILL EFFECTS AND HAS NOT SOUGHT OR RECEIVED ANY FOLLOW UP ATTENTION BEYOND THE INSTRUCTIONS GIVEN HIM. HE HAS NOT LOST ANYTIME FROM WORK AS A RESULT.

PALLETS CONTAINING CARTONS OF H/M WERE DOUBLE STACKED ON THE CARRIER'S DOCK. ONE PALLET FELL TO THE DOCK FLOOR, RESULTING IN DAMAGE TO FOUR CARTONS. ONE RECEPTACLE IN ONE CARTON FAILED ALLOWING LOSS OF ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS. CARRIER PERSONNEL HANDLED CLEAN UP OF THE SPILL.

THIS ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS ON PALLETS WITH THE EXCEPTION OF THREE DRUMS AT THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER, WHICH WERE ON THE FLOOR. CONSIGNEE PROVIDED THE DRIVER WITH A PALLET AND REQUIRED HIM TO PLACE THOSE THREE DRUMS ON IT. WHILE DOING SO THE DRIVER AND THE CONSIGNEE OBSERVED A SMALL QUANTITY OF PRODUCT BUBBLE OUT OF THE FILL BUNG AND ONTO THE DRUM HEAD. THE DRIVER EXAMINED THE HEAD AND BUNG AND WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT THE BUNG WAS CROSS-THREADED INTO ITS HOLE. CONSIGNEE, AFTER DISCUSSION WITH THE SHIPPER, REFUSED THE LEAKING DRUM BUT ACCEPTED THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT. DRIVER SECURED A SPILL PAD TO THE DRUM HEAD TO ABSORB ANYTHING THAT MIGHT ESCAPE ENROUTE. HE TOOK THE REFUSED DRUM WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY TO AWAIT SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.

column168: AFTER INITIAL REPORTS OF AIRBORNE LEAKAGE, CLOSE INSPECTION REVEALED A VISIBLE VAPOR LEAK IN THE AREA WHERE THE TANK CAR'S GAUGING DEVICE WAS SUPPOSED TO BE . IT APPEARS THAT SA SPLIT "O" RING UNDERNEATH THIS FLANGE PLATE WAS THE SOURCE OF LEAKAGE.  ER CONTRACTORS WERE HIRED TO INSTALL A CAPPING-KIT (C-KIT).  AFTER 4 DAYS OF VARIOUS METHODS OF CAPPING, PRESSURE REDUCTION AND TRANSFER COMBINATIONS, A STANDARD C-KIT WAS MODIFIED (IN ADDITION TO SOME STEEL REMOVAL IN THE VERY TIGHT DOME AREA) AND PROVED TO BE SUCCESSFUL IN CAPPING THE LEAK. WHEN THE CONSIGNEE AT THE LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT MURATA ELECTRONICS) REMOVED THEIR SHIPMENT,  LIQUID BEGAN RUNNING FROM A TOTE WHICH WAS TO BE DELIVERED TO A SUBSEQUENT STOP.  THE SPILLAGE WAS DETERMINED TO BE COMING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TOTE WHICH WAS FACING FORWARD.  IN THAT POSITION IT WAS NOT VISIBLE.  THE DRIVER STATES THAT THE CONSIGNEE DID NOT HIT THE TOTE AT ANY TIME.  THE MATERIAL HAD RUN ONTO THE ASPHALT DRIVEWAY AND SOME WAS RUNNING ONTO THEIR GRASS.  THE DRIVER PUT DOWN MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO ATTEMPT TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE.  HE AND MURATA EMPLOYEES BUILT A DAM OF OIL DRY AROUND MOST OF IT.  THE DRIVER BELIEVES THAT THEY CONTAINED MOST OF IT.  HE DID NOT SEE ANY ACCESS TO ANY WATERWAY. THE CARRIER RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE ALL  ASPECTS OF THE CLEAN UP.  WHEN THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON LOCATION, THEY PUMPED THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE TOTE INTO DRUMS, THEN TURNED THE TOTE ONTO ITS SIDE. THE CARRIER'S TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO REMAIN IN PLACE OVERNIGHT TO DRIP OUT INTO FASHIONED CONTAINMENTS.  THEN IT WAS MOVED TO THE CONTRACTOR'S PREMISES  FOR UNLOADING AND GROSS DECONTAMINATION.  THE CLEAN UP EXTENDED TWO ADDITIONAL DAYS, DURING WHICH TIME ALL OF THE FREIGHT WAS UNLOADED.  NEW PALLETS WERE PURCHASED AND ALL OF THE SHIPMENTS WERE TRANSFERRED TO THEM AFTER INSPECTION FOR CONTAMINATION.  ANOTHER TRAILER WAS ACQUIRED AND THE FREIGHT WAS PUT INTO IT FOR DELIVERY.  THE CONTRACTOR RETURNED TO THE INCIDENT LOCATION TO COMPLETE SITE MITIGATION.  THE FAILED PACKAGE AND THE DRUMMED MATERIAL FROM IT WERE RETURNED TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY FOR INSPECTION AND ULTIMATE RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.  IT APPEARS THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE OUTER SHELL FAILED AND CAVED IN FROM CORROSION, CAUSING THE RIGID PLASTIC LINER TO CRACK. THAT FAILURE ALLOWED ESCAPE OF THE PRODUCT.
ON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM A PINHOLE IN ITS BOTTOM.  THE CONSIGNEE BELIEVES THAT IT IS THE FAILURE OF A RECONDITIONED DRUM.  THEY ACCEPTED IT WITH A DAMAGE NOTATION.

column168: THE TRUCK DRIVER WAS CLIMBING A HILL AND WAS GOING AROUND 30 MPH.  ON TOP OF THE HILL, THERE WAS A CURVE.  THE DRIVER USED THE  BRAKES TO SLOW DOWN. HE WAS THEN GOING APPROX. 20 MPH. AT THE END OF THE CURVE, A CAR WAS COMING ON THE OTHER SIDE.  THE CAR WAS A LITTLE ON HIS SIDE OF THE ROAD WITH ONE WHEEL ON THE LANE.  THE TRUCK DRIVER GAVE A SMALL TURN TO THE RIGHT, ON THE WHEEL.  THE CAR DID THE SAME AND PASSED EACH OTHER WITH NO PROBLEM WHAT SO EVER.  BUT WHEN HE GAVE THE WHEEL A SMALL TURN TO THE RIGHT THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRUCK WENT ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  THE SHOULDER IS MADE OF SAND SO THE TRUCK SANK IN A LITTLE TO GET OUT OF THERE HE HAD TO GIVE THE WHEEL  A TURN TO THE LEFT.  WHEN ALL THE WHEEL WHERE BACK ON THE PAVEMENT THEY HAD TO GIVE THE WHEEL ANOTHER TURN TO THE RIGHT AND THAT IS WHEN HE SAW THE TANK TRAILER.  GOING UP IN THE AIR ON THE LEFT SIDE.  A FEW SECONDS LATER THE TRAILER AND THE TRUCK FELL ON THEIR RIGHT SIDES.  THE TRUCK DRIVER GOT OUT BY HIMSELF THROUGH THE WINDSHIELD.  HE WAS ALONE, A FEW MINUTES LATER PEOPLE STARTED ARRIVING.  THE TRUCK DRIVER WANTED TO GO AND STOP THE LEAKING BY PUTTING HIS JACKET IN THE HOLE.  BUT 2 MEN STOPPED HIM. THERE WAS ABSOLUTELY NO DANGER DOING THIS AND IT WOULD HAVE PREVENTED A LOT. PLUS LESS PRODUCT WOULD HAVE SPILLED.  BUT THE POLICE OFFICERS DIDN'T WANTED THE TRUCK DRIVER TO DO THIS THEY WERE SAYING IT WAS GOING TO EXPLODE, WHICH WAS NOT TRUE.  AFTER THIS THE TRUCK DRIVER LEFT TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL SO THE POLICE OFFICERS AND FIREMAN WHERE IN CHARGE.  WHEN THE PRODUCT STOPPED LEAKING OUT OF TRAILER, THEY PUT IT BACK ON ITS WHEELS THE CLEANING WAS DONE THE FOLLOWING DAYS.  OUR RECOMMENDATIONS:# 1 THAT THE POLICE OFFICERS AND FIREMEN SHOULD KNOW MORE ABOUT THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IF NOT THEY SHOULD HAVE SOME TRUST IN THE TRUCK DRIVERS THAT ARE CERTIFIED TO CARRY THOSE TYPE OF PRODUCTS AND HAVE ALL THE DOCUMENTATION TO PROVE IT AND KNOW WHAT THEY CARRY AND THE DANGER OF IT.  OUR RECOMMENDATIONS= #2 THEY SHOULD NOT PUT MATERIAL TO FILL THE SHOULDERS OF THE ROAD THAT IS SOFT AND CRUMBLES WITH THE WEIGHTS OF HEAVY VEHICLES.

column168: THE PROAM LP GAS BOBTAIL, (VEHICLE 1) WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON LA HWY 343 AT 0830 AT A ESTIMATED SPEED OF 45 MPH.  THE ROADWAY IS STRAIGHT, LEVEL AND WAS DRY.  THE WEATHER WAS CLEAR AND SUNNY.  THERE ARE NO OBSTRUCTIONS AT THE INTERSECTION.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 1 HAD JUST LEFT THE OFFICE AND WAS EN-ROUTE TO MAKE SEVERAL DELIVERIES.  A PASSENGER CAR (VEHICLE 2) WAS TRAVELING EAST ON LANDRY RD. THAT INTERSECTED LA HWY 343.  TRAFFIC ON LA HWY. 343 HAVE THE RIGHT OF WAY AND TRAFFIC ON LANDRY HAVE A STOP SIGN AT THE INTERSECTION.  VEHICLE 2 SLOWED BUT DID NOT MAKE A COMPLETE STOP AT THE INTERSECTION.  VEHICLE 1 SLOWED WHEN HE SAW THAT VEHICLE 2 HAD STOPPED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE INTERSECTION.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 2, A HANDICAPPED SENIOR CITIZEN, SEEMED CONFUSED AND MADE A ATTEMPT TO CROSS THE HIGHWAY BUT THEN STOPPED AGAIN.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 1 SLOWED AND SWERVED RIGHT IN AN ATTEMPT TO AVOID CONTACT.  AT A ESTIMATED SPEED OF THEN 30 MPH VEHICLE 1 MADE CONTACT WITH LEFT REAR CORNER OF VEHICLE 2 KNOCKING IT ACROSS THE INTERSECTION.  VEHICLE 1 THEN SLID INTO A EARTHEN STORM DITCH AND LAID OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE AT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE AGAINST THE HIGH SIDE OF THE DITCH. THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 1 EXITED THE TRUCK AND CHECKED FOR LEAKS.  HE RECEIVED MINOR BRUISES TO HIS RIGHT KNEE AND HIP AND A SMALL CUT ON HIS HAND.  HE THEN WENT TO CHECK ON THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 2 AND FOUND THAT THE FEMALE DRIVER WAS UNCONSCIOUS.  A PASSING MOTORIST CALLED 911 SERVICES AND ASSISTED THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 1 TO DIVERT TRAFFIC.  THE LA HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED OUT ALONG WITH A LIFE FLIGHT HELICOPTER AND AMBULANCE.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 2 WAS EVACUATED BY HELICOPTER.  THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 1 WAS TAKEN BY AMBULANCE TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM FOR OBSERVATION AND POST ACCIDENT DRUG AND ALCOHOL TESTING.  THOSE RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE.  THE LA HIGHWAY PATROL AND THE LA HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM CLOSED THE HIGHWAY AND RE-ROUTED TRAFFIC AT 0940.  THEY REQUESTED A WRECKER TO SERVICE TO UPRIGHT VEHICLE 1 AND REMOVE VEHICLE 2.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF VEHICLE 1 A VERY SMALL VAPOR LEAK WAS FOUND AT A FITTING ON THE CARGO TANK DELIVERY VALVE.  PROAM SERVICE TECHNICIANS WERE NOT ALLOWED TO STOP THE VAPOR LEAK WHICH ONLY REQUIRED THE RE-TIGHTENING OF THE FITTING.  THE LA HAZMAT TEAM LEADER REQUIRED THE CARGO TANK TO BE UNLOADED ON SITE BEFORE THE VEHICLE 1 COULD BE MOVED.  THIS TOOK OVER 4 HOURS FOR A TRANSPORT EQUIPPED WITH A PUMP TO BE LOCATED AND BROUGHT TO THE SITE AND ANOTHER 3 HOURS TO UNLOAD THE CARGO TANK.  BECAUSE OF THE ANGLE OF THE CARGO TANK ONLY 60% OF THE PRODUCT COULD BE REMOVED.  TWO WRECKERS AND A FOAM TRUCK FROM THE LAFAYETTE PARISH VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE THEN USED TO UPRIGHT THE VEHICLE. THE ROADWAY WAS RE-OPENED AT 1730 HOURS.  IT IS THE OPINION OF THE PROAM LOUISIANA, INC. ACCIDENT REVIEW BOARD THAT THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE 2 WAS AT FAULT AND THE PROAM DRIVER OF VEHICLE 1 MADE EVERY EFFORT TO AVOID THE ACCIDENT.  THE LOUISIANA HIGHWAY PATROL DID NOT ISSUE A CITATIO

ON AUGUST 14, 2000, AT 18:15 HOURS ENVIRONMENTAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND TECHNOLOGIES, INC. (EERT) WAS REQUESTED BY TH ST. JOSEPH FIRE DEPARTMENT TO RESPOND TO THE CORNER OF NORTH 10TH STREET AND CHURCH STREET IN ST. JOSEPH, MISSOURI FOR A REPORTED CHLORINE SPILL.  THE SOURCE OF SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF DRIVER HITTING A TREE ON NORTH 10TH STREET.  THUS, RIPPING THE SIDE OF THE BOX TRUCK OPEN.  DURING, THE IMPACT OF THE ACCIDENT THE LOAD INSIDE THE TRUCK SHIFTED AND BREAKING OFF A VALVE OFF THE BOTTOM OF ONE TOTE CONTAINING THE CHEMICAL OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION, CAUSING A RELEASE OF CHEMICAL ONTO THE ROADWAY TRAVELING NORTH ON 10TH STREET TO A OPEN STORM DRAIN.  EERT ARRIVED ON THE SITE AT 18:25 HOURS, MET WITH THE CITY OF ST. JOSEPH FIRE DEPARTMENT AND TOLD THEM WHAT THE CHEMICAL WAS IN THE TRUCK. EERT MADE A VISUAL ASSESSMENT OF THE INCIDENT AND DETERMINED THAT THE CHEMICAL WAS TRAVELING ALONG THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AS REPORTED TO AN OPEN STORM DRAIN, WHICH GOES DIRECTLY TO THE CITY OF ST. JOSEPH WASTEWATER TREATMENT PLANT.  EERT WAS INFORMED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT THE WASTEWATER TREATMENT PLANT HAD ALREADY BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AND THAT WE WERE ON SITE AND WOULD DILUTE THE RELEASE.  EERT PERSONNEL MADE ENTRY INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK AND UPRIGHTED THE TOTE IN A POSITION THAT WOULD PREVENT ANY FURTHER CHEMICAL FROM LEAKING OUT OF THE TOTE.  THUS, CAUSING FURTHER CONTAMINATION ONTO THE CITY STREETS.  EERT OBSERVED THAT THE VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF TOTE WAS SHEARED OFF FROM THE IMPACT ON THE TOTE CONTAINING THE CHEMICAL.  THE RESULT OF THE VALVE BEING SHEARED OFF CAUSED THE CHEMICAL TO DISCHARGE FROM THE TOTE.  EERT AFTER STOPPING THE LEAK AND SECURING THE REST OF THE LOAD ON THE TRUCK HAD EDWARD'S CHEMICAL PERSONNEL TRANSPORT THE TRUCK TO THEIR FACILITY ON MIDDLETON ROAD IN ST. JOSEPH, MISSOURI.  THIS WAS DONE WITH THE PERMISSION OF THE CITY OF ST. JOSEPH POLICE DEPARTMENT.  EERT THEN BEGAN TO CLEAN UP THE STREET BY PLACING ABSORBENT MATERIAL ALONG THE PATH WHERE THE CHEMICAL WAS TRAVELING.  ALL OF THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED ON SPILL WAS THEN PICKED UP AND PLACED INTO 55-GALLON DRUMS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  EERT MADE PROPER NOTIFICATIONS TO MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, BUCHANAN COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY AND THE LEPC.  THIS WAS DONE VIA MOBILE PHONE AT 18:58 HOURS AND WILL BE FOLLOWED UP WITH WRITTEN REPORTS.

column168: *  VAN LOAD OF 330GAL TOTES (QTY OF 10) *  HEADING NORTH ON HWY 113, ATTEMPTED TO TURN LEFT ONTO DORSET ST *  DURING LEFT TURN HIS TRAILER TIPPED AND PULLED THE TRACTOR WITH IT.
