NO OTHER VEHICLES OR PROPERTY WERE    INVOLVED. *  THE DIXON POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND BUILT A BERM ON BOTH ENDS OF THE ACCIDENT,    TRAPPING ANY SPILLED LIQUID IN THE GUTTER. *  DAVE JOHNSON AND JUAN ALFARO WERE DISPATCHED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SITE WITH THE SPILL KITS. *  OUR TANKER AND MINI BULK TRUCK WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. *  LANCE FROM TCI AND TOM GENT FOLLOWED CLOSE BEHIND IN ONE OF OUR STAKEBEDS WITH MORE OF THE    NEUTRALIZING AND ABSORPTION MATERIALS, INCLUDING EMPTY DRUMS. *  FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE *  APPROXIMATELY 4PM, ALL HASA DISPATCHED PERSONNEL WERE ON SITE AND INSTRUCTED TO WAIT FOR    FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL TO ARRIVE AND ASSESS THE SPILL WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT USING    SCBA EQUIPMENT.  THE DRIVER WAS DRIVEN FOR A VOLUNTARY "POST ACCIDENT" DRUG AND ALCOHOL    SCREEN. *   FOSS PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND FOSS PERSONNEL AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT MADE AN ASSESSMENT OF     THE SPILL. *  AFTER THIS ASSESSMENT THERE WAS A MEETING BETWEEN THE IC (INCIDENT COMMANDER, CAPTAIN AYALA,    FROM THE SACRAMENTO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM), FOSS, HASA PERSONNEL, AND OTHER    OFFICIALS, INCLUDING BRADLEY NICOLET, SOLANO COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT. *  IT WAS DECIDED THAT FOSS AND HASA COULD HANDLE THE CLEAN UP AND MOST OF THE AGENCIES WERE    SENT HOME. *  THE DIXON POLICE REMAINED:  DIXON FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE DIXON CITY WORKERS KEPT IN CONTRACT    AS NEEDED DURING THE CLEAN UP.  BRADLEY NICOLET ALSO REMAINED. *   FOSS AND HASA WORKERS BEGAN CLEAN UP AND RECOVERY OF PRODUCT STILL IN THE TRUCK.  THIS PROCESS BEGAN AROUND 9PM AND WAS COMPLETED BY 11PM.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 3200 GALLONS WAS RECOVERED. *  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE UPRIGHTED. *  THE LIQUID BETWEEN THE BERMS WAS NEUTRALIZED AND PUMPED INTO FOSS PROVIDED DRUMS.  THE DIRT USED FOR THE BERMS WERE ADDED TO THE DRUMS TO MAKE THE WASTE SOLID. *  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE PREPARED AND REMOVED TO THE DIXON YARD. *  THE STORM DRAIN DIRECTLY AT THE END OF THE TRAILER HAD SOME STANDING WATER IN IT.  IT WAS TESTED AND SHOWED A NORMAL PH.  ALTHOUGH THE PH WAS NORMAL, BRADLEY NICOLET DECIDED THAT THE STORM DRAIN MUST ALSO BE PUMPED. *  15 GALLONS OF WATER WAS PUMPED OUT OF THE STORM DRAIN, LEAVING IT EMPTY. BRADLEY NICOLET, ASSIST. FIRE CHIEF DRAYTON AND THE CITY WORKER DEEMED THAT IT WAS SUFFICIENTLY CLEANED. *  THE DIXON FIRE DEPARTMENT RINSED THE ENTIRE AREA WITH WATER AND IT WAS DEEMED "CLEAN" BY BRADLEY NICOLET AND ASSIST. FIRE CHIEF DRAYTON.  THE ROAD WAS REOPENED ABOUT 3AM. CORRECTIVE ACTION: *  FULL REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT WAS COMPLETED WITH THE DRIVER. *  ALL FUTURE SHIPMENTS OF

OUR DELIVERY DRIVER WAS FILLING HIS OIL TRUCK FROM OUR OWN TERMINAL.  HE THOUGHT THE TANK HAD 1,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL BUT IT HAD 5,100 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.  HE LEFT WITH ANOTHER OIL TRUCK AND DID A COUPLE OF DELIVERIES WITHIN A MILE OF THE GARAGE.  A CUSTOMER DROVE BY AND SAW THE DIESEL FUEL COMING OUT OF THE TOP OF THE TANK TRUCK.  HE WENT AND SHUT OFF THE VALVE.  HE CALLED OUR OFFICE AND TOLD US OF  THE ACCIDENT.  THE DRIVER WENT BACK TO THE TERMINAL AND I MET HIM THERE.  WE CALLED ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC. AND THE CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AT THIS TIME.  ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC. CAME AND CONTAINED THE SPILL THAT WENT INTO A WATER SPOT AREA BEHIND OUR TERMINAL.  WE ARE AT THIS TIME WORKING WITH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC. ON IMPLEMENTING A CONTAINMENT AREA FOR OUR TANK TRUCKS.  WE HAVE TOLD OUR DRIVERS NEVER TO LEAVE THE TRUCK AGAIN.

THE OIL DRAINED THROUGH THIS SYSTEM. THE TRAILER SCULLY SYSTEM WAS REPAIRED BY CONTRACTOR. OIL TRANSPORT DRIVERS ARE NOW USING THE DOUBLE CHECK SYSTEM TO PREVENT SETTING INCORRECT GALLONS ON LOADING METERS.

ON 08/02/2000 AT 0016, AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 208 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT:  ABX AIR, INC; 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS MIRANDA SOUTH AND BRUCE SHILTZ, ALONG WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR CHARLES JONES,DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY NOTICED A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX SHOWING SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE TOP CORNER OF THE PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THIS PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN INSPECTION.  UPON INSPECTION THEY FOUND 1 X 1 LITER GLASS BOTTLE OF ISOBUTYL ACETATE. THIS HAD A PLASTIC FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE, THAT HAD BROKEN INTO SEVERAL PIECES.  THIS WAS FOUND TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR AND LEAK.  THE LID DID HAVE A PLASTIC SEAL AROUND IT, WHICH IS STILL ATTACHED TO THE BOTTLE.  THIS GLASS BOTTLE WAS INSIDE OF A PLASTIC BAG SURROUNDED BY VERMICULITE, BUT STILL MANAGED TO LEAK TO THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX.  THEY REPLACED THE BOTTLE BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED THE BOX, AND PLACED IT INTO 3 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM, AND RETURNED THE LEAKING SHIPMENT TO THE PREDISIGNATED DESTINATION FOR LEAKING SHIPEMENTS WITH THIS SHIPPER.  THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THIS ODOR WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATION WERE RESUMED.  THE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS, AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0035.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment
column168: TANK CAR CHVX 290061 WS INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT AT BITTER CREEK WY. THE TANK CAR DID NOT ACTUALLY GET HIT IN THE DERAILMENT BUT IT DID RELEASE PRODUCT THROUGH THE LIQUID VALVE. ED BANKS AND KIM KNEELING, ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD MANAGERS, RESPONDED AND AFTER DISCUSSION WITH THE FRA, DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT WAS DUE TO LOOSE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID VALVE AND NOT THE RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT. MGR KEELING TIGHTENED THE LOOSE BOLTS AND BUBBLING AROUND THE VALVE STOPPED. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: AT 0600HRS ON 8-9-00, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER. THEY ADVISED THAT A CARMAN HAD DETECTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR TEIX 30062. THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED IN YARD 1, TRACK 411, 36ST YARD, DENVER COLORADO. UPON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH   NOTED A STRONG SMELL EMITTING FROM THE QUICK FILL HOLE COVER. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE QUICK FILL HOLE COVER GASKET WAS CRACKED AND IN POOR CONDITION. ADDITIONALLY, ALL THREE SWING BOLTS SECURING THE COVER PLATE WERE IN POSITION, LOOSE, AND FINGER TIGHT. MGR LERCH REMOVED FAULTY GASKET, AND REPLACED IT WITH A TEMPORARY GORTEX GASKET. THE QUICK FILL HOLD COVER WAS  THEN POSITIONED, AND PROPERLY SECURED. FURTHER INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED 1 OF 8 MAN WAY COVER SWING BOLTS TO BE IN POSITION, LOOSE, FINGER TIGHT. THE PLUG TO THE 3 INCH LIQUID VALVE WAS ALSO LOOSE, FINGER TIGHT, AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP WAS LOOSE 1/4 TURN. AFTER CORRECTING THE ABOVE EXCEPTIONS, MGR LERCH RELEASED CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION. THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE. NOTIFICATIONS: 1400HRS, 8-9-00, RON DUNBAR, PLANT MANAGER, SUTHERLAND ASSOCIATES, LLC.

column168: AFTER THE RETAINING PIN WAS BROKEN FROM THIS PACKAGE BEING DROPPED THERE WAS A RELEASE FROM THE INNER FIRE EXTINGUISHER CYLINDER.  THIS OCCURRED IN THE MEMPHIS SORT CENTER WHERE IT WAS CLEANED UP PER FEDEX POLICY BY THE SPILL CLEANUP GROUP.  THE SHIPMENT WILL REMAIN IN A SECURE LOCATION UNTIL DISPOSITION INFORMATION HAS BEEN RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

THE PACKAGE WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE THAT LED TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY WAS NOTICED.  THE PACKAGE WAS PART OF A FIVE PIECE SHIPMENT.  THE AFFECTED PACKAGE CONTAINED VARIOUS TYPES HOUSEHOLD CONSUMABLES INCLUDING FIVE AEROSOL CLEANING PRODUCTS, A BOTTLE OF RUBBING ALCOHOL, AND A BOTTLE OF TILEX.  ONE OF THE AEROSOLS INITIATED CAUSING THE LEAKAGE.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OF LABELS ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE BOX NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT STEVE LEE/FAA/ATL/CAFSO AT 17:35(CST) ON 08/16/2000.

FILE 3014D, SHPR:  PRINTSAFE, AWB# DGE 8313852256 KSS. ON 8/10/2000 AT 0201, A SPILL WITH A PAINT ODOR WAS REPORTED AT GATE A62, N801AX TOPSIDE, IN A RED C - CONTAINER OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIANS ELWOOD BOHL AND TIMOTHY HINES DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS LEAKING AND EMITTING AN ODOR.  THEY OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND BEGAN THEIR INSPECTION.  UPON THIS INSPECTION THEY FOUND 4X4 LITER PLASTIC BOTTLES INSIDE THIS FIBERBOARD BOX.  THIS LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 3 OUNCES.  THEY REPLACED ALL CONTENTS, RESEALED THE BOX, AND PLACED IT INSIDE OF 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM, AND FORWARDED THE DRUM ONTO IT'S DESTINATION.  THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THIS DID HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT.  THE AREA INVOLVED WITH THIS WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  THERE WAS SEVEN EMPLOYEES THAT NOTICED THE ODOR, THEY WERE ADVISED OF WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0230.

HAND TO SURFACE TECHNIQUE AND "NO AIR TIME" FOR ANY PACKAGE.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY TIM POST, MANAGER, INTERMODAL, ICTF, LONG BEACH, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  DEVELOPED THE CONTAINER WAS NOTED LEAKING AND BROUGHT TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION.  THE SUPPORTING WAYBILL INFORMATION SHOWED THE CONTENTS TO BE FAK, HOWEVER, WHEN OPENED, THE CONTENTS TURNED OUT TO BE 55 GALLON DRUMS OF A CLEANING COMPOUND SOLVENT CLASSIFIED AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF, INSPECTED THE CONTAINER, AND FOUND THE LADING VOID OF ANY BLOCKING AND BRACING.  THE DRUMS HAD BEEN DOUBLE STACKED WITH NO BILEVEL SEPARATION.  THIS IS NOT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE BOE 6C FOR THE LOADING AND SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES TRANSPORTED  BY RAIL.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE CONTAINER WAS VOID OF ANY TYPE OF PLACARDING.  APL WAS CONTACTED AND THEY PROVIDED THEIR SHIPPER, HAPAG LLOYD.  HAPAG LLOYD PROVIDED AN MSDS ON THE PRODUCT, AND STATED THEIR PAPERWORK SHOWED THE CONTENTS AS FLAMMABLE.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE SHIPPER, AND THE LADING WAS REMOVED TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM(S).  ONE DRUM FROM THE BOTTOM TIER, SECOND OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDE WALL WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THE DRUM CHIME WAS SITTING ON AN ELEVATED FLOOR SCREW THAT RUBBED THROUGH CAUSING A SLIGHT LEAK.  ESTIMATED LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS ONE GALLON.  THE SECOND LEAKING DRUM WAS LOCATED ON THE BOTTOM TIER, THIRD ROW IN FROM THE DOORS, SECOND OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDE WALL. BOTH THE TOP AND BOTTOM ROLLING HOOPS WERE DAMAGED FROM ABRADING AN ADJACENT DRUM.  ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS WAS SEVEN GALLONS. THE THIRD LEAKING DRUM WAS LOCATION IN THE THIRD ROW FROM THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, SECOND OUT FROM THE RIGHT SIDE WALL.  THE TOP ROLLING HOOP WAS DAMAGED FROM ABRADING AN ADJACENT DRUM. ESTIMATED PRODUCT LOSS  WAS NINE GALLONS. ALL THREE DRUMS WERE PATCHED,  PLACED INTO OVER PACKS AND SECURED.  WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, 22 ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE NOTED TO HAVE SUSTAINED DAMAGE THAT WARRENTED THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT.  ALL WERE PLACED INTO OVER PACKS TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL DAMAGE.  THE CONTAINER FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE USABLE DRUMS RELOADED INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE DAMAGED AND LEAKING DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER, PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS, WHERE THE PRODUCT COULD BE TRANSFERED TO NEW DRUMS. ONCE THE PRODUCT TRANSFER IS COMPLETED, THE DRUMS WILL BE SHIPPED BACK TO LONG BEACH, AND LOADED WITH THE EXISTING DRUMS.  THE CONTAINER WILL BE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO DESTINATION.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES,  AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: HARRY RODABOUGH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY RMCC THAT TANK CAR EDCX 6200 WAS VENTING AND EMITTING NITRIC ACID FUMES.  THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 9 AT THE PROVO YARD, UT. BOTH CHEMTREC AND ENSIGN BICKFORD, CONSIGNEE, WERE NOTIFIED. REPRESENTATIVES FROM ENSIGN BICKFORD RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND RELEASED THE VAPOR PRESSURE ON THE CAR UNTIL THE LEAK STOPPED.  THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY ATTACHING A TWO INCH HOSE TO THE AIR VALVE AND WASHING THE VAPORS THROUGH A FIVE GALLON DRUM OF WATER. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CAR DELIVERED IMMEDIATELY.

column168: ON AUGUST 29,2000, RAMP AGENTS AT PDX DISCOVERED A PASSENGER'S BAGGAGE THAT SMELLED OF GASOLINE AND HAD LIQUID LEAKING OUT THE END. UPON INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE, THE AGENTS DISCOVERED A CHAINSAW. THE DUFFEL BAG WAS CHECKED IN BDL AND TRANSFERRED IN PHX. THE GENTLEMAN INDICATED THAT HE THOUGHT HIS CHAINSAW WAS "DRY" AND THAT HE WAS SORRY FOR CAUSING ANY PROBLEMS. THE CHAINSAW WAS ESTIMATED TO CONTAIN LESS THAN A PINT OF FUEL, AND ALL MATERIALS WERE CLEANED UP AND ALLOWED TO VENTILATE. TO PREVENT SUCH A THING FROM REOCCURRING, SOUTHWEST HAS RECENTLY BEGUN AN INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL CUSTOMER AWARENESS CAMPAIGN. FOR EXTERNAL CUSTOMERS, WE HAVE A BROCHURE ENTITLED "THIS STUFF WON'T FLY" IN OUR AIRPORT TRAVEL CENTERS. WE HAVE ALSO USED THIS BROCHURE AS AN INTERNAL CUSTOMER (EMPLOYEE) AWARENESS TOOL AT SOUTHWEST FREEDOM EXPOS (INTERNAL CONVENTIONS HELD IN DAL, MDW AND PHX). ADDITIONALLY, WE HAVE BEGUN DISPLAYING HAZMAT POSTINGS AT THE STATIONS COVERING VARYING TOPICS. ENCLOSED IS A RECENT FLYER COVERING INTERNAL COMBUSTION ENGINES, WHICH IS DISTRIBUTED AS AN AWARENESS TOOL FOR OUR AGENTS AND INCLUDES CONTRACT SKYCAP AND CARGO EMPLOYEES. LASTLY, OUR RESERVATIONS SYSTEM AND TRAVEL AGENT INFORMATION HAS BEEN VERIFIED TO REFLECT THE INTERNAL COMBUSTION ENGINE POLICY AND BULLETIN UPDATES HAVE BEEN POSTED ON NUMEROUS DAYS TO REFLECT THIS POLICY.

column168: FILE:  2078D, SHIPPER:  WINANDY GREENHOUSE, AWB# DNT 4418975724RFD ON 08 -29 - 2000 AT 0501 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED AT GATE D45 ON AIRCRAFT N905AX AT BELLY 2; OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT;ABX AIR, INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE, Wilmington, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN ROBERT HARPER AND MICHEAL COOK AS WELL AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR TAMARA RAMIREZ, DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING 1 X 12OZ, METAL SPRAY CAN, SPRAY PAINT, CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE, OF WHICH LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 12OZS. THERE WAS ALSO SEVERAL METAL BARS IN THE SHIPMENT, ONE OF THE METAL BARS PUNCTURED THE CAN CAUSING THE LEAKAGE.  THE CONTENTS WERE PLACED BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED, AND THE SHIPMENT WAS PUT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE BAGGED PACKAGE WAS THAN PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS CHRISTI KIRKER AND DONALD OSBORNE ALSO ASSISTED ON THE SPILL.  THIS LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 1 OZ. ON THE BELLY FLOOR.  TRIPLE 5 SOLVENT AND DEGREASER WAS USED TO CLEAN THE BELLY FLOOR. THIS DID HOWEVER, STAIN THE FLOOR.  THE AREA INVOLVED WAS WELL VENTILATED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THERE WAS TWO EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THIS SHIPMENT, ODOR ONLY.  THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WITH EMPLOYEES.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS, OR SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO, OR ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL. A COPY OF THE SHIPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. CLEAR OF SCENE 0528.

column168: FLIGHT 674 DEPARTED GATE AT 1725L CREW COULD NOT START ENGINE #3, SO RETURNED TO GATE. AT GATE CREW NOTICED FUEL SMELL, + PASSENGER MICHAEL HORWICH VOLUNTEERED INFORMATION THAT THE SMELL MIGHT BE FROM HIS BACK PACK IN BIN (AFT) CAPTAIN HAD ALL PASSENGERS DISEMBARK AND EMERGENCY FIRE DEPT CALLED. NWA RAMP CREW LOCATED BACKPACK UNDER THE DIRECTION OF FIRECHIEF. FIRE DEPT OPENED BACKPACK AND FOUND A CAMPING STOVE FILLED WITH UNLEADED GAS AND MATCHES LOCATED NEXT TO IT. NWA REMOVED THE STOVE & MATCHES  FROM BACKPACK, POLICE TOOK REPORT FROM MR HORWICH. AFTER MECHANICAL PROBLEM RESOLVED. IT WAS DETERMINED BY POLICE, FIRE DEPT, CAPTAIN & NWA CHIEF PILOT THAT MR HORWICH WAS NOT A THREAT. ALL PASSENGERS, INCLUDING MR. HORWICH, WERE BOARDED AND FLIGHT COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. MR. HORWICH WAS COMPLETELY COOPERATIVE.

column168: ON 08/31/00 RMCC CONTACTED CTS MGR M. KELLY AND ADVISED THAT THE ABOVE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPORTED LEAKING IN THE CADIZ ST. YARD. AT DALLAS, TX  M. KELLY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THAT THE ABOVE CAR HAD LEAKED PRODUCT DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR ONTO THE TRACK AND DIRT ROAD NEXT TO THE CAR.  KELLY CONTACTED EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND REQUESTED THEY PROCEED TO THE SCENE AND ASSIST WITH THE CLEAN UP.  UPON THEIR ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS JUST ON THE SURFACE AND HAD NOT SOAKED IN TO THE GROUND. THE PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.  KELLY INSPECTED THE RAILCAR AND FOUND THAT THE VAPOR LINE VALVE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION AND THAT THE PLUG WAS OUT OF THE VALVE.  THE LIQUID INDUCTION VALVE WAS ALSO IN THE OPEN POSITION AND THE LIQUID VALVE CAP WAS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  KELLY CORRECTED BOTH PROBLEMS AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED DEAN COOPER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AT 8:50 PM BY THE COMMERCE, CA.  MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS THAT CONTAINER TRIU 969892 WAS FOUND LEAKING AND A CONTRACTOR WAS ENROUTE TO INVESTIGATE.  MICHAEL JOHNSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, REPORTED HE WAS EN ROUTE TO HANDLE THE INCIDENT.  MGR. JOHNSON STATED THE CONTAINER HELD PH OF 14 AND WAS DERAMPED AND ISOLATED.  HE REPORTED THE CONTAINER INVOLVED LEAKED ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT WITH SOME OF IT STILL INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  MR. JOHNSON STATED THE REST OF THE PRODUCT LEAKED ONTO CONTAINER PONU 716836 AND INTERMODAL STACK CAR DTTX 723670.  INSPECTION REVEALED ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD A TWO INCH BY THREE INCH PATCH APPLIED BEFORE TRANSPORT AND THE PATCH FAILED CAUSING THE LEAK.  A SECOND DRUM LEAKED AFTER THREE SCREW HEADS WORE A HOLE THROUGH THE DRUM.  BOTH DRUMS WERE OVER PACKED AND RELOADED.  CONTAINER TRIU 969892 WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH VINEGAR AND WATER AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  ALSO, CONTAINER PONU 716836 AND STACK CAR DTTX723670 WERE NEUTRALIZED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column168: REGO BERTON, CITE SUPERVISOR, REPORTED CONTAINER MOGU 255657 WAS LEAKING AN OILY LIQUID SUBSTANCE AND AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ON THE GROUND.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED ON A RAILCAR AT THE ICTF YARD.  MICHAEL JOHNSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MGR JOHNSON REPORTED THAT PRODUCT HAD LEAKED INSIDE THE CONTAINER AND ONTO THE FLATCAR.  THE SECUREMENT FOR THE DRUMS WAS INADEQUATE AND NOT PROPERLY APPLIED. MGR JOHNSON REPORTED THERE WAS A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM.  THE HOLE WAS CAUSED BY A LOOSE SCREW IN THE FLOOR BOARD OF THE CONTAINER.  THE HOLE WAS ONE QUARTER INCH WIDE AND A HALF INCH LONG.  THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOST WAS FIFTY-FIVE GALLONS.  SILBOND CORPORATION, THE MANUFACTURER, WAS CONTACTED THROUGH CHEMTEC AND ACCEPTED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE CLEANUP AND RELOADING OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS RELOADED AND PENDING DISPOSITION TO BE DETERMINED BY THE SHIPPER.

A WEDGE WAS PLACED BETWEEN THE CENTER SILL AND THE END OF THE CAR TO STOP THE LEAK. HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE OWNER OF THE CAR. HULCHER REMOVED THE BREECHED LINER AS WELL AS ALL RESIDUE PRODUCT LEFT IN THE CAR.
